<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

An **abstract class** in Object-Oriented Programming is a class that cannot be instantiated directly and is designed to serve as a **base class** (parent/superclass) from which other classes are derived. It is declared using the `abstract` keyword and may contain a combination of:

- **Abstract methods** — method signatures without an implementation body.
- **Concrete methods** — fully implemented methods with a body.
- **Data members (fields/attributes)**.
- **Constructors** (though they are invoked only by subclasses via `super()`).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Highlight:** An abstract class in Java represents a **partial implementation** — it captures common state and behaviour shared by a group of related classes while **deferring certain behaviours** (the abstract methods) to its subclasses for completion. This directly supports the OOP principles of **abstraction** and **polymorphism** in the KTU syllabus.

The general syntax in Java is:

```java
abstract class ClassName {
    // data members
    // concrete methods
    abstract returnType methodName(parameters);  // abstract method
}
```

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — The Blueprint View

Imagine a **"Vehicle Blueprint"** on an architect's table.

The blueprint is **not a real vehicle** — you cannot drive it. However, it defines:
- A standard structure (wheels, engine, chassis)
- Some finished sub-parts (the body shell design — a concrete method)
- Some placeholders that say *"the engine type will be specified later"* (an abstract method)

When a car company or a bike company **inherits** this blueprint, they:
- **Must** fill in the placeholder (the engine) — i.e., provide implementation for abstract methods.
- **May reuse** the standard structure — concrete methods.
- Each derived product (Car, Bike, Truck) **completes the blueprint in its own way**.

> [!NOTE]
> The blueprint = **Abstract Class**, the placeholders = **Abstract Methods**, and the finished vehicles = **Concrete Subclasses**.

## 1.3 Key Properties at a Glance

- Declared with the `abstract` keyword.
- **Cannot be instantiated** (`new AbstractClass()` → compile-time error).
- May contain **zero or more abstract methods**; if it contains even one, the class must be `abstract`.
- Can have **constructors**, but they are called only via `super()` from subclasses.
- Supports **single inheritance only** (in Java, a class extends exactly one class).
- Subclasses must implement **all inherited abstract methods** OR themselves be declared `abstract`.

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference

## 2.1 The "Why" Behind Abstract Classes

The fundamental purpose of abstraction is to:

1. **Hide implementation complexity** — the caller sees only the *what*, not the *how*.
2. **Enforce a contract** — every subclass *must* provide specific behaviour, otherwise compilation fails.
3. **Promote code reuse** — common code lives in the abstract class; variation lives in subclasses.
4. **Enable polymorphism** — references of the abstract type can hold any subclass object at runtime (dynamic binding).

## 2.2 Rules Governing Abstract Classes (KTU 2024 — High-Yield)

| # | Rule | Consequence if Violated |
|---|------|--------------------------|
| 1 | A class with at least one abstract method must be declared `abstract`. | Compile-time error |
| 2 | An abstract class **cannot be instantiated** directly. | Compile-time error: *"AbstractClass is abstract; cannot be instantiated"* |
| 3 | Abstract methods have **no body** — they end with a semicolon. | Compile-time error |
| 4 | A subclass must implement **all** inherited abstract methods, or be declared `abstract` itself. | Compile-time error in concrete subclass |
| 5 | Abstract classes **can** have constructors, but they are only called via `super()` from subclasses. | No direct invocation possible |
| 6 | Abstract classes **can** have `final` methods (cannot be overridden) and `static` methods. | Valid construct |
| 7 | Abstract classes **cannot** be `final` and **cannot** be `static` (final prevents inheritance, abstract requires it). | Compile-time error |

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Examiner Focus:** Question 4 of the rules above (subclass MUST implement or itself be abstract) is the **most frequently asked** rule in board exams. Memorize it.

## 2.3 Abstract Methods — The Contract

An abstract method is a method **signature** without an implementation. It establishes a **contract**: any non-abstract subclass *must* provide an implementation matching the signature.

**Formal Java Syntax:**

```java
abstract <return-type> <method-name>(<parameter-list>);
```

Key characteristics:
- Ends with a **semicolon** (not curly braces).
- Cannot be `private` (subclasses cannot override private methods).
- Cannot be `final` (final prevents overriding).
- Cannot be `static` (static methods cannot be overridden, only hidden).

## 2.4 Abstract Class vs Concrete Class — Comparison Matrix

| Feature | Abstract Class | Concrete Class |
|---------|----------------|----------------|
| `abstract` keyword | Required (if it has abstract methods) | Not used |
| Instantiation (`new`) | Not allowed | Allowed |
| Abstract methods | Allowed | **Not allowed** |
| Concrete methods | Allowed | Allowed |
| Constructors | Allowed (invoked by subclass) | Allowed |
| Use case | Base/template class | Fully implemented class |
| Object creation | Only via subclass reference | Direct |

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

Abstract classes are foundational in the following domains:

- **Framework Design** — Spring, Hibernate, and JavaFX use abstract base classes to define extension points.
- **GUI Libraries** — `java.awt.Graphics` is abstract; subclasses (`Graphics2D`) provide concrete drawing.
- **Template Method Pattern** — abstract class defines the algorithm skeleton; subclasses provide step implementations.
- **Plugin Architectures** — define an abstract plugin interface; third parties extend it.
- **Hardware Abstraction** — embedded systems use abstract base classes to model generic peripherals (sensor, actuator).

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations, Demonstrations & Analytical Examples

## 3.1 Worked Example 1 — Basic Abstract Class (Step-by-Step)

**Problem:** Model a generic `Shape` (abstract) with concrete subclasses `Circle` and `Rectangle`, each providing its own `area()`.

### Step 1 — Declare the abstract base class

```java
abstract class Shape {
    String color;

    // Concrete method — common to all shapes
    void setColor(String c) {
        color = c;
    }

    // Abstract method — every shape must define its area
    abstract double area();

    // Concrete method
    void displayColor() {
        System.out.println("Color: " + color);
    }
}
```

*Explanation:* `Shape` is abstract because it contains the abstract method `area()`. It also has a concrete method `setColor()` that is inherited as-is by all subclasses.

### Step 2 — Implement a concrete subclass

```java
class Circle extends Shape {
    double radius;

    Circle(double r) {
        radius = r;
    }

    @Override
    double area() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }
}
```

*Explanation:* `Circle` extends `Shape` and **must** provide an implementation of `area()`; otherwise, the compiler will reject `Circle` unless it is also marked `abstract`.

### Step 3 — Implement another concrete subclass

```java
class Rectangle extends Shape {
    double length, width;

    Rectangle(double l, double w) {
        length = l;
        width  = w;
    }

    @Override
    double area() {
        return length * width;
    }
}
```

### Step 4 — Driver class demonstrating polymorphism

```java
public class ShapeDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Shape s = new Shape();      // ❌ COMPILE-TIME ERROR
        Shape c = new Circle(5.0);     // ✅ Upcasting — valid
        Shape r = new Rectangle(4.0, 6.0);

        c.setColor("Red");
        r.setColor("Blue");

        System.out.println("Circle area    : " + c.area());
        System.out.println("Rectangle area : " + r.area());
        c.displayColor();
        r.displayColor();
    }
}
```

### Step 5 — Trace the Output

```
Circle area    : 78.53981633974483
Rectangle area : 24.0
Color: Red
Color: Blue
```

*Explanation:* The reference type is `Shape` (abstract), but at runtime the JVM dispatches the call to the actual subclass's `area()` — this is **runtime polymorphism (dynamic method dispatch)**.

## 3.2 Worked Example 2 — Abstract Class with Constructor

**Problem:** Show that an abstract class can have a constructor and how it is invoked through `super()`.

```java
abstract class Employee {
    String name;
    int    id;

    Employee(String n, int i) {            // constructor
        name = n;
        id   = i;
        System.out.println("Employee constructor called");
    }

    abstract double calculateSalary();

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name + ", ID: " + id);
    }
}

class FullTimeEmployee extends Employee {
    double monthlySalary;

    FullTimeEmployee(String n, int i, double s) {
        super(n, i);                       // calls abstract-class constructor
        monthlySalary = s;
    }

    @Override
    double calculateSalary() {
        return monthlySalary;
    }
}

class PartTimeEmployee extends Employee {
    double hourlyRate;
    int    hours;

    PartTimeEmployee(String n, int i, double rate, int h) {
        super(n, i);
        hourlyRate = rate;
        hours      = h;
    }

    @Override
    double calculateSalary() {
        return hourlyRate * hours;
    }
}
```

**Driver snippet:**

```java
Employee e1 = new FullTimeEmployee("Anu",  101, 50000.0);
Employee e2 = new PartTimeEmployee("Ravi", 102, 300.0,  40);

e1.display();
System.out.println("Salary: " + e1.calculateSalary());

e2.display();
System.out.println("Salary: " + e2.calculateSalary());
```

*Explanation:* Each time a concrete subclass object is created, the `super(n, i)` call **implicitly chains** to the abstract class constructor first, initializing the inherited fields. This is a classic KTU exam pattern.

## 3.3 Mathematical/Logical Derivation — Why "abstract" is a compile-time constraint

The Java compiler enforces the contract through the following logical chain:

$$
\text{Class } C \text{ is abstract} \iff \text{Class } C \text{ has at least one method } m \text{ such that } \text{body}(m) = \emptyset
$$

$$
\text{Subclass } S \text{ is valid (concrete)} \iff \forall m \in \text{AbstractMethods}(C), \; \exists \; m' \in S : \text{signature}(m') = \text{signature}(m) \;\wedge\; \text{body}(m') \neq \emptyset
$$

**Translation:**
- A class is `abstract` **if and only if** it has at least one method without a body.
- A concrete subclass is valid **if and only if** for every abstract method inherited, it provides a method with the **same signature** and a **non-empty body**.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Board Tip:** When asked *"Can an abstract class have no abstract methods?"* — the answer is **YES**. The reverse is not true: a class with even one abstract method **must** be declared abstract.

## 3.4 Common Pitfall Analysis

```java
abstract class A { abstract void f(); }

class B extends A { }   // ❌ Compile error — B must implement f()
abstract class C extends A { }   // ✅ Valid — C is also abstract
class D extends A { void f() { } }   // ✅ Valid
```

*Explanation:* If a subclass does not implement all abstract methods, the subclass itself must be marked `abstract` — this propagates the responsibility up the inheritance chain until a concrete class implements every abstract method.

<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

