# 4. Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 Class Hierarchy Diagram (Mermaid)

```mermaid
graph TD
    nodeA["Abstract Shape"]:::abstractNode
    nodeB["Circle"]:::concreteNode
    nodeC["Rectangle"]:::concreteNode
    nodeD["area abstract method"]:::abstractMeth
    nodeE["setColor concrete method"]:::concreteMeth
    nodeF["override area PI r squared"]:::concreteMeth
    nodeG["override area length times width"]:::concreteMeth

    nodeA --- nodeD
    nodeA --- nodeE
    nodeB --- nodeF
    nodeC --- nodeG
    nodeA --> nodeB
    nodeA --> nodeC

    classDef abstractNode fill:#FFE4B5,stroke:#FF8C00,stroke-width:2px,color:#000
    classDef concreteNode fill:#E0F8E0,stroke:#2E8B57,stroke-width:2px,color:#000
    classDef abstractMeth fill:#FFFACD,stroke:#B8860B,stroke-dasharray:5 5,color:#000
    classDef concreteMeth fill:#F0F8FF,stroke:#4682B4,stroke-width:1px,color:#000
```

**How to read this diagram:**

- The **yellow node** (`Abstract Shape`) is the base class.
- The **green nodes** (`Circle`, `Rectangle`) are concrete subclasses.
- The **dashed-border node** (`area abstract method`) denotes a method that is *declared but not implemented* in the base class.
- The **blue nodes** are *concrete method implementations* in the subclasses.
- Arrows point from superclass to subclass (generalization relationship).

## 4.2 Block-Level Functional Architecture Flow — Object Construction with Abstract Class

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    node1["Caller invokes: new Subclass args"]:::start
    node2["JVM allocates memory for Subclass object"]:::process
    node3["Subclass constructor begins execution"]:::process
    node4["super call invokes AbstractClass constructor"]:::process
    node5["AbstractClass fields initialized"]:::process
    node6["AbstractClass constructor body executes"]:::process
    node7["Control returns to Subclass constructor"]:::process
    node8["Subclass fields initialized"]:::process
    node9["Subclass constructor body executes"]:::process
    node10["Object fully constructed and returned"]:::end
    node11["Polymorphic call: ref.area resolves at runtime to actual subclass implementation"]:::polymorph

    node1 --> node2 --> node3 --> node4 --> node5 --> node6 --> node7 --> node8 --> node9 --> node10 --> node11

    classDef start fill:#FFD700,stroke:#B8860B,stroke-width:2px,color:#000
    classDef process fill:#E6E6FA,stroke:#6A5ACD,stroke-width:1px,color:#000
    classDef end fill:#90EE90,stroke:#228B22,stroke-width:2px,color:#000
    classDef polymorph fill:#FFB6C1,stroke:#DC143C,stroke-width:2px,color:#000
```

**Reading guide:** This flow illustrates that even though you cannot `new AbstractClass()` directly, the abstract class's constructor **does execute** as part of the subclass's instantiation chain. This is a frequent KTU exam question.

