# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1
**[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**
**Define an abstract class in Java. Can an abstract class be instantiated? Justify your answer.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
An abstract class in Java is a class declared with the `abstract` keyword that may contain abstract methods (methods without a body) as well as concrete methods. It serves as a base class providing a common structure and partial implementation for its subclasses. (2 marks)

An abstract class **cannot be instantiated** directly using the `new` operator. This is because an abstract class may have unimplemented methods, and the JVM cannot determine the behaviour of such an object. Therefore, `new AbstractClass()` results in a **compile-time error**. Objects are created only through concrete subclasses. (1 mark)

---

### Question 2
**[KTU University Exam – June 2024]**
**Can an abstract class contain a constructor? If yes, explain when and how it is invoked.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
Yes, an abstract class can contain a constructor. (0.5 marks)

The constructor is **not** invoked by creating an object of the abstract class (since that is illegal). It is invoked implicitly through the `super()` call from the constructor of a concrete subclass during object creation. (2 marks)

This mechanism allows the abstract class to **initialize its own data members** (common to all subclasses) before the subclass-specific fields are initialized. (0.5 marks)

---

## 5.2 Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks, Module Internal Choice)

### Question A (14 Marks)

**[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023, Model QP]**

**(a)** Explain the concept of abstract classes in Java with a suitable example. Discuss the rules that must be followed while using abstract classes. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java program to create an abstract class `BankAccount` with abstract method `calculateInterest()` and concrete method `display()`. Derive two subclasses `SavingsAccount` and `CurrentAccount` that implement the abstract method appropriately. Demonstrate polymorphism using an array of `BankAccount` references. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Model Solution — Part (a)

**Concept (2 marks):**
An abstract class is a partially implemented class declared with the `abstract` keyword. It acts as a template for related classes. It may declare one or more abstract methods (signatures only, no body) which **must** be implemented by any concrete subclass, or the subclass itself must be declared abstract. Abstract classes support the OOP principle of **abstraction** by hiding implementation details and exposing only essential behaviour.

**Rules (3 marks):**
1. A class with at least one abstract method must be declared `abstract`.
2. Abstract classes cannot be instantiated.
3. Abstract methods have no body — they end with a semicolon.
4. A subclass must implement all inherited abstract methods, or be declared `abstract`.
5. Abstract classes can have constructors, fields, and concrete methods.
6. `final` and `abstract` cannot be combined (since `final` prevents the inheritance that `abstract` requires).

**Example (2 marks):**

```java
abstract class Animal {
    abstract void sound();          // abstract method
    void sleep() {                  // concrete method
        System.out.println("Sleeping...");
    }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Bark");
    }
}
```

---

#### Model Solution — Part (b)

**Java Program (7 marks):**

```java
abstract class BankAccount {
    String accountHolder;
    double balance;

    BankAccount(String name, double bal) {
        accountHolder = name;
        balance       = bal;
    }

    abstract double calculateInterest();      // abstract — to be defined per account type

    void display() {                            // concrete method
        System.out.println("Holder: " + accountHolder
                         + ", Balance: " + balance
                         + ", Interest: " + calculateInterest());
    }
}

class SavingsAccount extends BankAccount {
    double rate = 0.04;   // 4% per annum

    SavingsAccount(String n, double b) { super(n, b); }

    @Override
    double calculateInterest() {
        return balance * rate;
    }
}

class CurrentAccount extends BankAccount {
    double rate = 0.02;   // 2% per annum

    CurrentAccount(String n, double b) { super(n, b); }

    @Override
    double calculateInterest() {
        return balance * rate;
    }
}

public class BankDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BankAccount[] accounts = new BankAccount[2];
        accounts[0] = new SavingsAccount("Anu",  100000);
        accounts[1] = new CurrentAccount("Ravi", 200000);

        for (BankAccount acc : accounts) {
            acc.display();   // polymorphic dispatch
        }
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Holder: Anu,  Balance: 100000.0, Interest: 4000.0
Holder: Ravi, Balance: 200000.0, Interest: 4000.0
```

**Explanation (within 7 marks):** The `BankAccount` array holds references of the abstract type. At runtime, the JVM resolves `calculateInterest()` to the appropriate subclass implementation, demonstrating **dynamic polymorphism**.

---

### Question B (14 Marks) — Alternative Choice

**[KTU University Exam – June 2024, Model QP]**

**(a)** Differentiate between abstract class and concrete class in Java. Can an abstract class have all concrete methods? Justify. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Design an abstract class `Vehicle` with fields `brand` and `speed`, an abstract method `fuelType()`, and a concrete method `displayDetails()`. Derive `Car` and `Bike` classes, each implementing `fuelType()`. Write a complete Java program and explain how the abstract class enforces a contract. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Model Solution — Part (a)

**Comparison Table (4 marks):**

| Abstract Class | Concrete Class |
|----------------|----------------|
| Declared with `abstract` keyword | Declared normally |
| Cannot be instantiated | Can be instantiated |
| May contain abstract methods | Cannot contain abstract methods |
| Used as base class | Used for object creation |
| Supports partial implementation | Supports full implementation |

**"All concrete methods" question (3 marks):**
Yes, an abstract class **may** have zero abstract methods — i.e., all its methods may be concrete. The `abstract` keyword is still legal and meaningful because:
- It **prevents direct instantiation** of the class.
- It signals the developer's intent that the class is intended only as a base class.

**Example:**
```java
abstract class Helper {
    void greet() { System.out.println("Hello"); }   // concrete only
}
```

---

#### Model Solution — Part (b)

```java
abstract class Vehicle {
    String brand;
    int    speed;

    Vehicle(String b, int s) {
        brand = b;
        speed = s;
    }

    abstract String fuelType();           // contract — must be implemented

    void displayDetails() {               // concrete — inherited as-is
        System.out.println("Brand: " + brand
                         + ", Speed: " + speed + " km/h"
                         + ", Fuel: " + fuelType());
    }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    Car(String b, int s) { super(b, s); }

    @Override
    String fuelType() {
        return "Petrol or Diesel";
    }
}

class Bike extends Vehicle {
    Bike(String b, int s) { super(b, s); }

    @Override
    String fuelType() {
        return "Petrol";
    }
}

public class VehicleDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Vehicle v1 = new Car("Toyota", 180);
        Vehicle v2 = new Bike("Yamaha", 120);
        v1.displayDetails();
        v2.displayDetails();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Brand: Toyota, Speed: 180 km/h, Fuel: Petrol or Diesel
Brand: Yamaha, Speed: 120 km/h, Fuel: Petrol
```

**Contract Explanation (within 7 marks):**
The `abstract` method `fuelType()` establishes a **contract**: any concrete subclass *must* provide its own implementation. The Java compiler enforces this — if `Car` or `Bike` omitted `fuelType()`, the code would **fail to compile**. This is the power of compile-time abstraction enforcement.

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Pitfalls — Where Students Lose Marks:**
> 1. **Forgetting the `abstract` keyword** on a class that has abstract methods → entire program fails to compile (-3 to -5 marks).
> 2. **Writing a body for an abstract method** (e.g., `abstract void f() { }`) → compile-time error (-2 marks).
> 3. **Trying `new AbstractClass()`** in code snippets → examiner marks this as a fundamental conceptual error.
> 4. **Mixing up `abstract` with `interface`** — remember: abstract class can have **state (fields)** and **constructors**; an interface (pre-Java 8) cannot.
> 5. **Not invoking `super(...)`** explicitly in the subclass constructor when the abstract class has a parameterized constructor → implicit `super()` fails to match → compile error.
> 6. **Forgetting `@Override` annotation** is not a compilation error, but **KTU examiners expect** it in the answer to demonstrate clarity (-1 mark style deduction).

---

## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **Definition:** An abstract class is declared using the `abstract` keyword and cannot be instantiated; it may contain abstract methods (signatures only) and concrete methods (with body).
- **Purpose:** Provides a **partial implementation** and **enforces a contract** for its subclasses.
- **Abstract Method:** A method declared without a body, ending with a semicolon — must be implemented by every concrete subclass.
- **Instantiation Rule:** `new AbstractClass()` is **illegal** at compile-time.
- **Constructor Rule:** Abstract classes **can** have constructors; they execute via `super()` when a subclass object is created.
- **Subclass Rule:** Concrete subclass must implement **all** inherited abstract methods **or** itself be declared `abstract**.
- **Keywords Forbidden with `abstract`:** `final` and `static` (for methods) — they contradict the purpose of abstraction.
- **Polymorphism:** Abstract class references can point to any subclass object, enabling **dynamic method dispatch**.
- **Common Use:** Base classes in frameworks, template method design pattern, GUI libraries (e.g., `java.awt.Graphics`).
- **Single Inheritance:** A class can extend **only one** abstract class (in Java), but can implement **multiple** interfaces — a key contrast.
- **Abstract vs Interface (quick memory aid):** Abstract class = "is-a" relationship with **shared code**; Interface = "can-do" capability contract with **no shared state** (pre-Java 8).
- **KTU 2024 Hot Questions to Expect:**
  1. "Can an abstract class have a constructor?" → **Yes**, via `super()`.
  2. "Can an abstract class have all concrete methods?" → **Yes**, but instantiation is still blocked.
  3. "What happens if a subclass does not implement all abstract methods?" → The subclass **must** itself be declared `abstract`.
  4. "Differentiate abstract class and interface" — most repeated Part B question.

<!-- SECTION_5_END -->

