# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 Structural Rules of an Interface (Bullet Logic)

### 2.1.1 Declaration Syntax

```java
[access_modifier] interface InterfaceName [extends OtherInterface1, OtherInterface2] {
    // 1. Constants (implicitly public static final)
    int MAX = 100;

    // 2. Abstract methods (implicitly public abstract)
    void method1();
    double compute(int x);

    // 3. Default methods (Java 8+) — has body
    default void defaultMethod() {
        System.out.println("Default implementation");
    }

    // 4. Static methods (Java 8+) — has body, called via interface name
    static void utilityMethod() {
        System.out.println("Static utility");
    }

    // 5. Nested types
    interface NestedInterface { void nestedMethod(); }
}
```

### 2.1.2 Implicit Modifiers (Must Memorize for KTU)

| Element | Implicit Modifiers | Can Be Changed? |
|---------|--------------------|-----------------|
| Variables in interface | `public static final` | No |
| Methods (pre-Java 8) | `public abstract` | No |
| Default methods | `public` (must have body) | Cannot reduce visibility |
| Static methods | `public` (must have body) | Cannot reduce visibility |
| Interface itself | `abstract` | No |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU High-Yield Rule:** Since interface methods are *implicitly public*, an implementing class **cannot** reduce visibility (e.g., declare the method as `protected` or `private`). It **must** be `public`.

### 2.1.3 Implementation Syntax

```java
[access_modifier] class ClassName [extends SuperClass]
                       [implements Interface1, Interface2, ...] {
    // Must provide body for ALL abstract methods of each interface
    @Override
    public void method1() {
        // implementation logic
    }

    // Optional: override default method
    @Override
    public void defaultMethod() {
        // customized behavior
    }
}
```

## 2.2 The "Why" Behind Each Rule

| Rule | Reason (Why) |
|------|--------------|
| All variables are `public static final` | Interfaces are *contracts*, not *state holders*. Variables become compile-time constants shared by all implementers. |
| All abstract methods are `public` | Any code holding an interface reference must be able to call its methods. |
| A class can implement **multiple** interfaces | Provides multiple-inheritance of *type* (capability) while avoiding *Diamond Problem* of state. |
| An interface can **extend** multiple interfaces | Allows building interface hierarchies (e.g., `Collection` → `List` → `ArrayList`). |
| Interfaces cannot be instantiated | They are abstract; the JVM cannot create an object of an incomplete type. |
| Default methods introduced in Java 8 | To allow **interface evolution** (adding new methods to existing interfaces like `List` without breaking all implementers). |
| Static methods in interface (Java 8) | To provide **utility methods** related to the interface, co-located with it (e.g., `Comparator.comparing(...)`). |

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Formula / Rule | Notes |
|---------|---------------|-------|
| Implementing interfaces | `class A implements I1, I2, I3` | Class **must** implement *all* abstract methods |
| Extending interfaces | `interface I3 extends I1, I2` | Inherits *all* abstract & default methods |
| Diamond Problem resolution | Use `InterfaceName.super.method()` | Explicitly disambiguate overriding default method |
| Functional Interface | Exactly **1** abstract method | Annotated with `@FunctionalInterface` |
| Marker Interface | **0** methods | Only metadata tag |
| Lambda requirement | Target type must be **functional interface** | `Runnable r = () -> System.out.println("Hi");` |
| Access modifier for implementation | **Must be `public`** | Cannot reduce visibility |
| Object of interface | `InterfaceName ref = new ImplementingClass();` | Polymorphic reference |

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **JDBC API:** `Connection`, `Statement`, `ResultSet` are interfaces. Vendors (MySQL, Oracle) provide implementations.
- **Collection Framework:** `List`, `Map`, `Set` are interfaces. `ArrayList`, `HashMap` are implementations.
- **Dependency Injection (Spring Framework):** Beans depend on *interfaces*, not concrete classes → easier testing and swapping.
- **Strategy Design Pattern:** Family of algorithms encapsulated behind an interface (`PaymentStrategy`, `SortStrategy`).
- **Callback Mechanisms:** `Runnable`, `Callable`, `ActionListener` — all functional interfaces.
