# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Worked Example 1 — Basic Interface Implementation

### Problem Statement
Design an interface `Shape` with method `area()` and `perimeter()`. Implement it using classes `Circle` and `Rectangle`. Demonstrate polymorphism.

### Step-by-Step Solution

**Step 1 — Declare the Interface**

```java
public interface Shape {
    // Implicitly public static final
    double PI = 3.14159;

    // Implicitly public abstract
    double area();
    double perimeter();
}
```

**Step 2 — Implement with `Circle`**

```java
public class Circle implements Shape {
    private double radius;

    public Circle(double radius) {
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override
    public double area() {
        return PI * radius * radius;
    }

    @Override
    public double perimeter() {
        return 2 * PI * radius;
    }
}
```

**Step 3 — Implement with `Rectangle`**

```java
public class Rectangle implements Shape {
    private double length, width;

    public Rectangle(double length, double width) {
        this.length = length;
        this.width = width;
    }

    @Override
    public double area() {
        return length * width;
    }

    @Override
    public double perimeter() {
        return 2 * (length + width);
    }
}
```

**Step 4 — Demonstrate Polymorphism via Interface Reference**

```java
public class ShapeDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Interface reference = implementation object
        Shape s1 = new Circle(5.0);
        Shape s2 = new Rectangle(4.0, 6.0);

        printReport(s1);  // Circle details
        printReport(s2);  // Rectangle details
    }

    public static void printReport(Shape s) {
        System.out.println("Area      = " + s.area());
        System.out.println("Perimeter = " + s.perimeter());
    }
}
```

**Step 5 — Expected Output**

```
Area      = 78.53975
Perimeter = 31.4159
Area      = 24.0
Perimeter = 20.0
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Why this is "polymorphism":** The method `printReport(Shape s)` accepts **any** `Shape`. The same call (`s.area()`) invokes **different** code based on the actual runtime object. This is the **Liskov Substitution Principle** in action.

## 3.2 Worked Example 2 — Interface Inheritance (Multiple Interface Extension)

### Problem Statement
Create interface `Drawable` (with `draw()`) and `Resizable` (with `resize(double factor)`). Create a child interface `Shape2D` that extends **both**. Implement using a class `Square`.

### Step-by-Step Solution

```java
// Parent Interface 1
public interface Drawable {
    void draw();
}

// Parent Interface 2
public interface Resizable {
    void resize(double factor);
}

// Child Interface inheriting from both
public interface Shape2D extends Drawable, Resizable {
    double area();
    double perimeter();
}

// Concrete Implementation
public class Square implements Shape2D {
    private double side;

    public Square(double side) {
        this.side = side;
    }

    @Override
    public void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a square of side " + side);
    }

    @Override
    public void resize(double factor) {
        if (factor <= 0)
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Factor must be positive");
        this.side *= factor;
    }

    @Override
    public double area() {
        return side * side;
    }

    @Override
    public double perimeter() {
        return 4 * side;
    }
}
```

### Analytical Derivation of Method Count

The class `Square` must implement:

$$
\text{Required methods} = \underbrace{1}_{\text{Drawable}} + \underbrace{1}_{\text{Resizable}} + \underbrace{2}_{\text{Shape2D}} = 4 \text{ methods}
$$

Each method **must** be `public` (cannot be reduced from interface's implicit `public`).

## 3.3 Worked Example 3 — Diamond Problem Resolution with Default Methods

### Problem Statement
Two interfaces provide **conflicting default methods** with the same signature. Show how a class can resolve this using `InterfaceName.super.method()`.

### Step-by-Step Solution

```java
public interface Printer {
    default void print() {
        System.out.println("Printer default print");
    }
}

public interface Scanner {
    default void print() {
        System.out.println("Scanner default print");
    }
}

// Class MUST override print() to resolve ambiguity
public class AllInOne implements Printer, Scanner {
    @Override
    public void print() {
        // Option A: Choose one
        Printer.super.print();

        // Option B: Combine both
        // System.out.println("Custom multi-function print");
    }
}
```

### Compile-Time Analysis

If a class implements two interfaces with conflicting default methods **and does not override**, the compiler raises:

$$
\text{Error: } \texttt{“class AllInOne inherits unrelated defaults for print() from types Printer and Scanner”}
$$

## 3.4 Worked Example 4 — Functional Interface and Lambda

### Step-by-Step Solution

```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Calculator {
    int operate(int a, int b);
}

public class CalculatorDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Lambda 1: Addition
        Calculator add = (a, b) -> a + b;

        // Lambda 2: Multiplication
        Calculator mul = (a, b) -> a * b;

        System.out.println("10 + 5 = " + add.operate(10, 5));
        System.out.println("10 * 5 = " + mul.operate(10, 5));
    }
}
```

**Output**

```
10 + 5 = 15
10 * 5 = 50
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Examiner Insight:** The annotation `@FunctionalInterface` is **not mandatory** for the interface to be functional — it is only a *compiler-enforced documentation marker*. However, KTU questions often test the rule: **exactly one abstract method**.

## 3.5 Interface vs Abstract Class — Comparative Analytical Matrix

This is a **guaranteed 14-mark question** in KTU exams. Master the comparison.

| Feature | Interface (Pre-Java 8) | Abstract Class | Interface (Java 8+) |
|---------|------------------------|----------------|---------------------|
| Keyword | `interface` | `abstract class` | `interface` |
| Method types | Only abstract | Abstract + concrete | Abstract + default + static |
| Variables | `public static final` only | Any access, any modifier | `public static final` only |
| Inheritance | A class can implement **many** | A class can extend **only one** | A class can implement many |
| Constructor | ❌ Cannot have | ✅ Can have | ❌ Cannot have |
| State (instance variables) | ❌ No | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| Access modifiers for methods | Implicitly `public` | Any (`public`, `protected`, `private` concrete) | `public` (default/static) |
| When to use | Define a **capability/role** (e.g., `Serializable`) | Define a **common base with shared code/state** | Define a **capability with shared default behavior** |
| Object instantiation | ❌ Cannot | ❌ Cannot | ❌ Cannot |

**Design Heuristic (KTU favorite):**

$$
\text{Is-A (Identity)} \rightarrow \text{Abstract Class} \qquad
\text{Can-Do (Capability)} \rightarrow \text{Interface}
$$

Example:
- `Dog` **is-a** `Animal` → **Abstract class** (shared state: `age`, `name`)
- `Dog` **can-do** `Runnable`, `Trainable`, `Pet` → **Interfaces** (capabilities)
