# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1 [KTU University Exam — May 2024, Model]

**Q: Define an interface in Java. Why can't an interface be instantiated?**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**

An **interface** in Java is a reference type declared using the `interface` keyword that defines a *contract* of abstract method signatures (and since Java 8, default and static methods). It is implicitly `abstract` and used to achieve **abstraction** and **multiple inheritance of type**.

An interface **cannot be instantiated** because:
1. It may contain **incomplete abstract methods** (no method body) — calling them would have no executable code.
2. Java disallows creating objects of any `abstract` type (a class or interface) directly.
3. Interfaces exist only to be **implemented** by classes, which then provide the concrete behavior.

To use an interface, we must:
- Either create a class that `implements` the interface and provides all abstract method bodies, **or**
- Use an **anonymous inner class** or a **lambda expression** (for functional interfaces).

Example:
```java
Drawable d = new Circle();  // OK: Circle implements Drawable
// Drawable d = new Drawable(); // COMPILE ERROR
```

---

### Question 2 [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023, Model]

**Q: What is a functional interface? Give one example from Java standard library.**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**

A **functional interface** is an interface that contains **exactly one abstract method**. It may have any number of `default` or `static` methods. Functional interfaces are the target type for **lambda expressions** and **method references**.

The annotation `@FunctionalInterface` is optional but recommended — the compiler will throw an error if the interface ends up with more than one abstract method.

**Example from Java Standard Library:**

```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Runnable {
    void run();   // single abstract method
}
```

Usage with a lambda:
```java
Runnable task = () -> System.out.println("Running task");
new Thread(task).start();
```

Other examples: `Comparable<T>` (with `compareTo`), `Comparator<T>` (with `compare`), `Callable<V>`, `ActionListener`.

---

## 5.2 Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks, with Internal Choice)

### Question A [14 Marks] [KTU University Exam — May 2024 Pattern]

**Q: (a)** Explain the concept of interfaces in Java. Discuss how multiple inheritance is achieved through interfaces. Illustrate with an example program. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Differentiate between abstract class and interface in Java. Under what circumstances would you prefer one over the other? **(7 Marks)**

#### Model Solution

#### (a) Concept of Interfaces and Multiple Inheritance

**Definition (1 mark):**  
An interface in Java is a reference type, declared with the `interface` keyword, that can contain abstract methods, default methods (Java 8+), static methods (Java 8+), and constants. It represents a *contract* that implementing classes must follow.

**Multiple Inheritance via Interfaces (3 marks):**  
Java does not support multiple inheritance of **classes** (to avoid the *Diamond Problem* of state). However, it allows a class to **implement multiple interfaces**, achieving multiple inheritance of **type (behavior)**. A class can extend one parent class and implement any number of interfaces simultaneously.

Syntax:
```java
class MyClass extends ParentClass implements I1, I2, I3 {
    // must provide concrete code for ALL abstract methods
    // declared in I1, I2, and I3
}
```

**Illustrative Program (3 marks):**

```java
// Two unrelated interfaces
interface Printable {
    void print();
}

interface Scannable {
    void scan();
}

// Class implementing BOTH interfaces — multiple inheritance
class MultiFunctionDevice implements Printable, Scannable {
    private String document;

    public MultiFunctionDevice(String doc) {
        this.document = doc;
    }

    @Override
    public void print() {
        System.out.println("Printing: " + document);
    }

    @Override
    public void scan() {
        System.out.println("Scanning: " + document);
    }
}

public class InterfaceDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MultiFunctionDevice mfd = new MultiFunctionDevice("Report.pdf");

        Printable p = mfd;   // Upcasting to Printable
        Scannable s = mfd;   // Upcasting to Scannable

        p.print();
        s.scan();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Printing: Report.pdf
Scanning: Report.pdf
```

**Key Takeaway:** The same object (`mfd`) can be treated as **multiple types** (`Printable` and `Scannable`) — this is multiple inheritance of behavior.

---

#### (b) Abstract Class vs Interface

**Comparison Table (4 marks):**

| Feature | Abstract Class | Interface |
|---------|----------------|-----------|
| Keyword | `abstract class` | `interface` |
| Multiple inheritance | ❌ No (only one parent) | ✅ Yes (implement many) |
| Method types | Abstract + concrete | Abstract + default + static |
| Instance variables | ✅ Yes (any type) | ❌ No (only `public static final` constants) |
| Constructor | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| Access modifiers for methods | Any (`public`, `protected`, `private` for concrete) | Implicitly `public` |
| When to use | Shared **state and behavior** among related classes | Define a **role or capability** for unrelated classes |

**When to Prefer (3 marks):**

- **Prefer Abstract Class** when:
  - Classes share a **common state** (instance variables) and a **partial implementation**.
  - You want to enforce a **template method pattern** with non-public helper methods.
  - The relationship is *is-a* (identity), e.g., `Dog` is-a `Animal`.

- **Prefer Interface** when:
  - Unrelated classes need to share a **capability** (e.g., many classes can be `Serializable`).
  - You need **multiple inheritance of type**.
  - The relationship is *can-do* (capability), e.g., `Dog` can-do `Runnable`, `Trainable`.
  - You want **maximum loose coupling** in your design (Strategy, Observer patterns).

**Conclusion:** In modern Java, both can carry concrete behavior. The choice hinges on whether the relationship describes **shared identity with state** (abstract class) or **shared capability without state** (interface).

---

### Question B [14 Marks] [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023 Pattern — Alternative Choice]

**Q: (a)** Explain the use of `default` methods in interfaces introduced in Java 8. How do they help in interface evolution? Write a program showing a class that overrides a default method. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** What is a marker interface? Explain with suitable examples from Java standard library. Also explain the role of `Comparable` interface with a working example. **(7 Marks)**

#### Model Solution

#### (a) Default Methods in Interfaces (Java 8)

**Concept (2 marks):**  
A `default` method in an interface is a method that has a **concrete implementation** (body) within the interface itself. It is declared using the keyword `default`. Default methods allow interfaces to provide **common reusable code** that all implementing classes inherit automatically, but classes are free to **override** them if needed.

**Role in Interface Evolution (2 marks):**  
Before Java 8, adding a new abstract method to a published interface (e.g., `List`) would break **all existing implementations** in the world. With default methods, new methods can be added to interfaces with a default body, ensuring **backward binary compatibility** — old classes continue to compile and run, while new code can use the new method or override it.

**Program (3 marks):**

```java
interface Vehicle {
    void start();

    // Default method — has body
    default void honk() {
        System.out.println("Beep! Beep! (Default horn)");
    }
}

class Car implements Vehicle {
    private String model;

    public Car(String model) {
        this.model = model;
    }

    @Override
    public void start() {
        System.out.println(model + " engine started.");
    }

    // Overriding the default method
    @Override
    public void honk() {
        System.out.println(model + " says: POOOONK!");
    }
}

class Bike implements Vehicle {
    @Override
    public void start() {
        System.out.println("Bike kick-started.");
    }
    // honk() inherited from interface — no override
}

public class DefaultDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Vehicle v1 = new Car("Honda City");
        Vehicle v2 = new Bike("Royal Enfield");

        v1.start();
        v1.honk();   // Calls overridden version

        v2.start();
        v2.honk();   // Calls interface default
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Honda City engine started.
Honda City says: POOOONK!
Bike kick-started.
Beep! Beep! (Default horn)
```

**Diamond Problem with Defaults:**  
If a class implements two interfaces that both define a `default` method with the same signature from **unrelated parents**, the compiler will throw an error. The class **must override** the method or explicitly call `InterfaceName.super.method()`.

---

#### (b) Marker Interface and `Comparable`

**Marker Interface (3 marks):**  
A **marker interface** is an interface that has **no methods or constants** at all. Its sole purpose is to *mark* or *tag* a class as having a particular property. The JVM or framework code uses `instanceof` checks to detect this tag and grant special behavior.

**Examples from Java Standard Library:**

1. **`java.io.Serializable`** — Marks a class whose objects can be converted to byte streams (e.g., for saving to disk or sending over network).
2. **`java.lang.Cloneable`** — Marks a class whose objects can be cloned using `Object.clone()`.
3. **`java.rmi.Remote`** — Marks a class whose methods can be invoked from a different JVM.

```java
import java.io.Serializable;

public class Student implements Serializable {
    private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;
    private String name;
    private int rollNo;

    public Student(String name, int rollNo) {
        this.name = name;
        this.rollNo = rollNo;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Student{name='" + name + "', rollNo=" + rollNo + "}";
    }
}
```

Usage:
```java
public class SerializeDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        Student s = new Student("Anu", 42);
        // JVM checks: if (s instanceof Serializable) -> allowed
        java.io.ObjectOutputStream oos = 
            new java.io.ObjectOutputStream(new java.io.FileOutputStream("s.dat"));
        oos.writeObject(s);
        oos.close();
        System.out.println("Object serialized.");
    }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Note:** If `Student` did *not* implement `Serializable`, the `writeObject()` call would throw `java.io.NotSerializableException`.

**Comparable Interface (4 marks):**  
`Comparable<T>` is a **functional interface** with a single abstract method `compareTo(T o)`. It defines the **natural ordering** of objects of a class. Classes that implement `Comparable` can be sorted using `Collections.sort()` or `Arrays.sort()`.

```java
public class Employee implements Comparable<Employee> {
    private String name;
    private double salary;

    public Employee(String name, double salary) {
        this.name = name;
        this.salary = salary;
    }

    @Override
    public int compareTo(Employee other) {
        // Natural order: ascending by salary
        return Double.compare(this.salary, other.salary);
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return name + " (Rs. " + salary + ")";
    }
}

public class ComparableDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        java.util.List<Employee> list = new java.util.ArrayList<>();
        list.add(new Employee("Ravi", 55000));
        list.add(new Employee("Anu", 72000));
        list.add(new Employee("Mohan", 48000));

        java.util.Collections.sort(list);   // Uses compareTo internally

        System.out.println("Sorted by salary (ascending):");
        for (Employee e : list) {
            System.out.println(e);
        }
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Sorted by salary (ascending):
Mohan (Rs. 48000.0)
Ravi (Rs. 55000.0)
Anu (Rs. 72000.0)
```

**Return value of `compareTo`:**
- Negative → `this` is *less than* `other`
- Zero → `this` is *equal to* `other`
- Positive → `this` is *greater than* `other`

