## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mistakes Where Students Lose Marks (KTU 2024 Pattern):**
>
> 1. **Forgetting to write `public` on implementing methods** — interface methods are implicitly `public`; if the class declares them as `void area()` (package-private), the compiler treats it as a **new method**, not an override. The class is then **abstract** and cannot be instantiated. **(Lose 1–2 marks)**
>
> 2. **Reducing visibility of an interface method** — writing `protected void draw()` in the implementing class is a **compile error**.
>
> 3. **Confusing `interface` and `class` declarations** — interfaces cannot have constructors; trying to write a constructor in an interface is a syntax error.
>
> 4. **Incorrectly stating that interfaces support multiple inheritance of state** — interfaces allow multiple inheritance of **type/behavior**, not **state**. This distinction is tested in 7-mark questions.
>
> 5. **Ignoring Diamond Problem** — when answering default methods, students often forget to mention the `InterfaceName.super.method()` resolution syntax.
>
> 6. **Forgetting `@Override` annotation** — not a compile error, but examiners deduct marks for *not following best practices*.
>
> 7. **Confusing functional interface with SAM type terminology** — KTU often uses both; remember they mean the same thing: **Single Abstract Method**.
>
> 8. **Confusing `Comparable` (natural order, one way) with `Comparator` (external, many ways)** — `compareTo` vs `compare`. This is a **favourite trick question**.

---

## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist — Interfaces (Module 1)**
>
> ✅ An **interface** is a contract: only abstract methods (pre-Java 8) + default/static methods (Java 8+) + `public static final` constants.
>
> ✅ Interfaces **cannot be instantiated**; they must be **implemented** by classes or **extended** by other interfaces.
>
> ✅ All interface variables are **implicitly `public static final`** (constants).
>
> ✅ All interface methods (pre-Java 8) are **implicitly `public abstract`**.
>
> ✅ A class can implement **any number** of interfaces — this is how Java achieves **multiple inheritance of type**.
>
> ✅ An interface can **extend multiple** parent interfaces.
>
> ✅ Implementing methods must be declared **`public`** — visibility cannot be reduced.
>
> ✅ **Default methods** (Java 8) provide a default body; classes can override them.
>
> ✅ **Static methods** in interfaces belong to the interface itself; called via `InterfaceName.staticMethod()`.
>
> ✅ **Functional Interface** = exactly **one** abstract method (eligible for lambda). Annotation: `@FunctionalInterface` (optional but recommended).
>
> ✅ **Marker Interface** = **zero** methods. Examples: `Serializable`, `Cloneable`, `Remote`.
>
> ✅ **Diamond Problem** with default methods: resolve using `InterfaceName.super.method()`.
>
> ✅ **`Comparable<T>.compareTo(T o)`** → natural ordering; negative/zero/positive return.
>
> ✅ **`Runnable`** has a single method `run()`; used by `Thread` for concurrent execution.
>
> ✅ **Use interface** for *can-do* capabilities; **use abstract class** for *is-a* shared identity with state.
>
> ✅ Interfaces enable **loose coupling**, **polymorphism**, and **plug-and-play** architectures (Strategy, Observer, Dependency Injection).
