## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Static Members

**Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology):**
A `static` member in Java is a class-level member (variable or method) that belongs to the **class itself** rather than to any individual object (instance). It is declared using the keyword `static` and is shared across all instances of the class. Memory for static members is allocated **once**, in the **Method Area / Class Area** of the heap, when the class is loaded by the ClassLoader.

Components of static members:
- **Static Variable (Class Variable):** A single shared copy across all objects.
- **Static Method:** Can be invoked without creating an object; can only directly access other static members.
- **Static Block:** Used for static initialization; executes once at class loading time.
- **Static Nested Class:** A class declared as a member of the outer class with the `static` modifier.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Board Highlight:** Static members are stored in the **Method Area** (part of the heap in modern JVMs), whereas instance members live in the **Young Generation** (heap). This is a frequently asked 3-mark question.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> A `static` method **cannot** use `this` or `super` keywords because there is no specific instance context to refer to. It can only directly call other static methods and access static data.

**Conceptual Analogy:**
Think of a university (the **class**). Every student is an **object**. The university name is a **static variable** — it is the same for all students and exists at the university level. A student's roll number is an **instance variable** — unique per student. A static method is like the "University Notice Board Read" function — you can use it without enrolling as a student.

---

### 1.2 Final Variables

**Formal Definition:**
The `final` keyword in Java is a non-access modifier used to **restrict** modification. When applied to:
- **Variable:** The value cannot be reassigned after initialization (a constant).
- **Method:** The method cannot be overridden by subclasses.
- **Class:** The class cannot be subclassed (no inheritance possible).

A `final` variable, once initialized, becomes a **compile-time constant** (if initialized with a literal) or a **blank final variable** (if not initialized at declaration but in constructor/initializer block).

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Highlight:** A `final` reference variable means the **reference** cannot change, but the **object's internal state** (its fields) can still be modified. This distinction is regularly tested.

**Conceptual Analogy:**
A `final` variable is like a **permanent marker label on a box**. You can change what is *inside* the box, but you cannot glue the label onto a *different* box. The reference (label) is fixed, the contents (object state) are not.

---

### 1.3 Inner Classes

**Formal Definition:**
An **Inner Class** (also called a *nested class*) is a class defined within another class in Java. It is a member of the enclosing class and has access to all members (including private) of the outer class.

The four types as per the KTU 2024 OOP syllabus are:
1. **Member Inner Class** — A non-static class defined at the member level of the outer class.
2. **Static Nested Class** — A static class defined as a member of the outer class.
3. **Local Inner Class** — A class defined inside a method or block.
4. **Anonymous Inner Class** — A class without a name, declared and instantiated in a single expression; typically used to override methods of an interface or class on the fly.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Board Exam Note:** Anonymous inner classes are heavily tested in event-handling and callback scenarios. In Java 8+, **lambda expressions** provide a more concise alternative, but anonymous classes are still part of the KTU 2024 syllabus.

**Conceptual Analogy:**
An inner class is like a **specialized department inside a company**. The department (inner class) has full access to company resources (outer class members), but the company itself does not need to be reorganized to accommodate it. It is logically grouped with the outer class.

---

### 1.4 Inheritance — Super Class & Sub Class

**Formal Definition:**
**Inheritance** is the OOP mechanism by which one class (called the **subclass**, **derived class**, or **child class**) acquires the properties and behaviors (fields and methods) of another class (called the **superclass**, **base class**, or **parent class**).

In Java, inheritance is declared using the `extends` keyword for classes:

```java
class SuperClass { /* ... */ }
class SubClass extends SuperClass { /* ... */ }
```

The `Object` class in `java.lang` is the **root superclass** of every Java class — either directly or indirectly.

**Conceptual Analogy:**
Inheritance is like **genetics**. A child (subclass) inherits traits (methods/fields) from a parent (superclass), but can also have its own unique traits (additional methods/fields) and even override inherited behaviors (method overriding).

---

### 1.5 Types of Inheritance

| Type | Description | Supported in Java? |
|------|-------------|-------------------|
| **Single** | One subclass inherits from one superclass | ✅ Yes |
| **Multilevel** | Chain: A → B → C | ✅ Yes |
| **Hierarchical** | Multiple subclasses inherit from one superclass | ✅ Yes |
| **Multiple** | One class inherits from multiple parents | ❌ No (use interfaces) |
| **Hybrid** | Combination of two or more types | ❌ No (use interfaces) |

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Board Classic:** "Why doesn't Java support multiple inheritance through classes?" — **Answer:** To avoid the **Diamond Problem** (ambiguity when two parents have the same method). Java solves this with **interfaces**, which support default methods since Java 8.

---

### 1.6 The `super` Keyword

**Formal Definition:**
`super` is a reference variable in Java used to refer to the **immediate parent class object**. It has three primary uses:
1. `super()` — Calls the parent class constructor.
2. `super.variable` — Accesses a parent class field (especially when hidden by a subclass field).
3. `super.method()` — Calls a parent class method (especially when overridden).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **`super()` must be the first statement** in a constructor. If you don't write it explicitly, the compiler **automatically inserts** a call to the parent's **no-argument constructor** (`super();`).

---

### 1.7 `protected` Members

**Formal Definition:**
`protected` is an **access modifier** in Java that allows access within:
- The same class,
- Same package (package-private + protected behavior),
- Subclasses (in any package, but only through inheritance).

Access modifier hierarchy from most to least restrictive:
`private` < `default` (package-private) < `protected` < `public`

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Subtle KTU Point:** A `protected` member is accessible to a subclass **only through inheritance** (i.e., inside a method of the subclass, or as `this.protectedMember`). It is **NOT** accessible via a parent-class reference from outside the package.

---

### 1.8 Calling Order of Constructors

**Formal Definition:**
In Java, when a subclass object is created, **constructors are called in a chain from the topmost superclass down to the subclass**. This is called **constructor chaining**. The call happens because every constructor implicitly (or explicitly) begins with `super()` or an overloaded constructor call `this()`.

Execution order:
1. Static members of the superclass (top-down)
2. Static members of the subclass
3. Instance initialization & constructor of the superclass
4. Instance initialization & constructor of the subclass

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Favorite:** A common exam question is — *"What is the output of the following program involving inheritance and constructors?"* — Answering correctly requires understanding this exact order.

**Conceptual Analogy:**
Imagine building a multi-story house. The foundation (superclass constructor) must be laid **first**, then the floors (subclass constructor) are built on top. You cannot build the upper floors before the foundation.
