## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 Static Members — Operational Rules

- **Loading Phase:** Static variables & static blocks are executed in the order they appear in the source code, **at class loading time** (before any object is created).
- **Access:** Static members are accessed using the class name (`ClassName.staticMember`), though instance access via an object reference is also allowed (with a compiler warning in modern IDEs).
- **Inheritance:** Static methods can be **hidden** (not overridden) in subclasses. Method resolution at compile time uses the **reference type**, not the object type.
- **Main Method:** `public static void main(String[] args)` is `static` so the JVM can invoke it **without instantiating the class**.

**Rules Checklist:**
- ✅ A static method can call only static methods directly.
- ✅ A static method can access only static data directly.
- ❌ A static method **cannot** use `this` or `super`.
- ❌ A static method **cannot** be overridden (it can only be hidden).

---

### 2.2 Final Variables — Deep Rules

- **Final local variable:** Cannot be reassigned; must be definitely assigned before use.
- **Final instance variable:** Must be assigned in **every** constructor, or in an initializer block, or at declaration.
- **Final static variable:** Must be assigned in a static block or at declaration. Convention: written in `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`.
- **Final parameter:** Cannot be modified inside the method.
- **Final method:** Cannot be overridden. Can be **overloaded** (different parameters).
- **Final class:** Cannot be extended. Examples: `String`, `java.lang.Math`, all wrapper classes (`Integer`, `Double`, etc.).

---

### 2.3 Inner Classes — Detailed Classification

**Member Inner Class:**
- Cannot declare static members (until Java 16 allowed some).
- Requires an outer class instance to be instantiated: `Outer outer = new Outer(); Outer.Inner inner = outer.new Inner();`

**Static Nested Class:**
- Declared `static` inside outer class.
- Can be instantiated without an outer instance: `Outer.StaticNested obj = new Outer.StaticNested();`
- Cannot access non-static members of the outer class directly.

**Local Inner Class:**
- Defined inside a method/block; scope is limited to that block.
- Can access `final` or *effectively final* local variables of the enclosing method.
- Cannot be declared `public`, `private`, `protected`, or `static` (with rare exceptions).

**Anonymous Inner Class:**
- Declared and instantiated in one expression using `new InterfaceName() { ... }` or `new ClassName() { ... }`.
- Used to provide one-off implementations, especially for event listeners and callbacks.
- Cannot have explicit constructors (uses instance initializer blocks if needed).

---

### 2.4 Inheritance — Access Modifier Implications

| Modifier | Same Class | Same Package | Subclass (any package) | Other Packages |
|----------|:----------:|:------------:|:----------------------:|:--------------:|
| `private` | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ |
| `default` | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ |
| `protected` | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ (via inheritance) | ❌ |
| `public` | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |

---

### 2.5 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Syntax | Memory/Behavior | Restriction |
|---------|--------|-----------------|-------------|
| Static Variable | `static int count;` | 1 copy per class | Cannot access instance members |
| Static Method | `static void show(){}` | 1 copy per class | No `this`/`super` |
| Static Block | `static { /* code */ }` | Runs once on class load | Cannot throw checked exceptions unhandled |
| Final Variable | `final int X = 10;` | Constant after init | Cannot reassign |
| Final Method | `final void run(){}` | Cannot be overridden | Can be overloaded |
| Final Class | `final class A {}` | Cannot be subclassed | No inheritance |
| Member Inner Class | `class Inner {}` | Needs outer instance | Cannot have static members (pre-Java 16) |
| Static Nested Class | `static class Inner {}` | No outer instance needed | Cannot access non-static outer members |
| Local Inner Class | inside method | Block-scoped | Limited scope |
| Anonymous Inner Class | `new I() { ... }` | One-time use | No named constructor |
| `super()` | first line of constructor | Calls parent constructor | Must be first statement |
| `super.x` | member access | Accesses parent field | Resolves hidden fields |
| `super.m()` | method call | Calls parent method | Resolves overridden methods |
| `protected` | member access | Package + subclass | Subclass access only via inheritance |
| Constructor Order | top-down chain | Super → Sub | `super()` auto-inserted |

---

### 2.6 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Static Members:** Used in **Singleton Design Pattern** (private static instance), counters, constants (`Math.PI`), factory methods, utility classes (`Collections`, `Arrays`).
- **Final Variables:** Used in **immutable class design** (e.g., `String`, `LocalDateTime`), configuration constants, thread-safe shared data.
- **Inner Classes:** Used in **GUI event handling** (Swing, JavaFX), **Adapter Classes**, **Callback implementations**, and **Builder Design Pattern**.
- **Inheritance:** Core of **polymorphism**, framework extensibility (e.g., extending `HttpServlet` in Java EE, extending `Activity` in Android).
- **`super` Keyword:** Critical in **template method pattern** and for calling parent constructors in frameworks like Spring.
- **`protected`:** Used in **framework design** so subclasses can hook into internal logic (e.g., `AbstractProcessor` in annotation processing).
- **Constructor Order:** Essential in **dependency injection frameworks** and understanding the lifecycle of beans in Spring/Java EE.
