## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Demonstrating Static Members — Complete Worked Example

```java
class Student {
    static String university = "KTU Kerala";
    static int count = 0;
    int rollNo;
    String name;

    Student(String name) {
        this.name = name;
        count++;
        this.rollNo = count;
    }

    static void showUniversity() {
        System.out.println("University: " + university);
        // System.out.println(name); // ❌ COMPILE ERROR: non-static field 'name'
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Roll " + rollNo + ": " + name + " (" + university + ")");
    }
}

public class StaticDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student.showUniversity();
        Student s1 = new Student("Anu");
        Student s2 = new Student("Ravi");
        s1.display();
        s2.display();
        System.out.println("Total Students: " + Student.count);
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Execution Trace:**

1. JVM loads `StaticDemo` class. `main` method starts.
2. `Student.showUniversity()` is called → prints "University: KTU Kerala".
3. `new Student("Anu")` is called:
   - `count` becomes **1**.
   - `s1.rollNo = 1`.
4. `new Student("Ravi")` is called:
   - `count` becomes **2**.
   - `s2.rollNo = 2`.
5. `s1.display()` prints: `Roll 1: Anu (KTU Kerala)`.
6. `s2.display()` prints: `Roll 2: Ravi (KTU Kerala)`.
7. `Student.count` prints: `Total Students: 2`.

> [!NOTE]
> The variable `university` is **shared** — it belongs to the class, not the objects. If any object modifies it (e.g., `s1.university = "MIT"`), all objects see the change. `count` is also shared and acts as a counter.

---

### 3.2 Demonstrating Final Variables — Worked Example

```java
class Circle {
    final double PI = 3.14159;
    final int RADIUS;
    String color;

    Circle(int r, String c) {
        this.RADIUS = r;     // blank final assigned in constructor
        this.color = c;
    }

    final double area() {
        return PI * RADIUS * RADIUS;
    }

    // void area(int x) {} // ✅ Allowed (overloading)
    // @Override
    // double area() { return 0; } // ❌ COMPILE ERROR: cannot override final
}

final class Constants { /* Cannot be extended */ }

// class MathExt extends Constants {} // ❌ COMPILE ERROR
```

**Step-by-Step Analysis:**

$$
\text{Area} = \pi \cdot r^2
$$

For `Circle(5, "Red")`:
- `RADIUS = 5` (assigned via constructor).
- `area() = 3.14159 × 5 × 5 = 78.53975`.

**Key Takeaways:**
- `PI` is a compile-time constant (initialized at declaration).
- `RADIUS` is a **blank final** — must be assigned in every constructor exactly once.
- `area()` is `final` — cannot be overridden in a subclass.
- `Constants` is a `final` class — cannot be extended.

---

### 3.3 Demonstrating Inner Classes — All Four Types

```java
class Outer {
    private int outerField = 100;
    static int staticField = 200;

    // 1. Member Inner Class
    class MemberInner {
        void show() {
            System.out.println("outerField = " + outerField);
            System.out.println("staticField = " + staticField);
        }
    }

    // 2. Static Nested Class
    static class StaticNested {
        void show() {
            // System.out.println(outerField); // ❌ cannot access non-static
            System.out.println("staticField = " + staticField);
        }
    }

    void method() {
        final int localVar = 50;

        // 3. Local Inner Class
        class LocalInner {
            void show() {
                System.out.println("localVar = " + localVar);
            }
        }
        new LocalInner().show();

        // 4. Anonymous Inner Class
        Runnable r = new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                System.out.println("Anonymous run() called");
            }
        };
        r.run();
    }
}

public class InnerClassDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Outer outer = new Outer();
        // Member inner
        Outer.MemberInner mi = outer.new MemberInner();
        mi.show();

        // Static nested
        Outer.StaticNested sn = new Outer.StaticNested();
        sn.show();

        // Local + Anonymous
        outer.method();
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Output Trace:**

$$
\text{Output} =
\begin{cases}
\texttt{outerField = 100} \\
\texttt{staticField = 200} \\
\texttt{staticField = 200} \\
\texttt{localVar = 50} \\
\texttt{Anonymous run() called}
\end{cases}
$$

**Construction Logic Table:**

| Inner Class Type | Outer Instance Needed? | How to Instantiate |
|------------------|:---------------------:|--------------------|
| Member Inner | ✅ Yes | `outerObj.new MemberInner()` |
| Static Nested | ❌ No | `new Outer.StaticNested()` |
| Local Inner | ✅ Yes (enclosing method) | `new LocalInner()` inside method |
| Anonymous | ✅ Yes | `new InterfaceName() { ... }` inline |

