### 3.4 Demonstrating Inheritance, `super`, and Constructor Order

```java
class Animal {
    String type = "Animal";
    static int animalCount = 0;

    static {
        System.out.println("1. Animal static block");
    }

    {
        System.out.println("2. Animal instance block");
    }

    Animal() {
        System.out.println("3. Animal constructor");
        animalCount++;
    }

    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes a sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    String type = "Dog";
    static int dogCount = 0;

    static {
        System.out.println("4. Dog static block");
    }

    {
        System.out.println("5. Dog instance block");
    }

    Dog() {
        super();   // Calls Animal() — implicit if not written
        System.out.println("6. Dog constructor");
        dogCount++;
    }

    @Override
    void sound() {
        super.sound();      // calls parent method
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }

    void showTypes() {
        System.out.println("Subclass type: " + this.type);
        System.out.println("Superclass type: " + super.type);
    }
}

public class InheritanceDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("--- Creating Dog ---");
        Dog d = new Dog();
        d.sound();
        d.showTypes();
        System.out.println("Animal count: " + Animal.animalCount);
        System.out.println("Dog count: " + Dog.dogCount);
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Execution Trace:**

1. **Class loading phase (when `Dog` class is first referenced):**
   - `Animal` static block executes → prints `1. Animal static block`.
   - `Dog` static block executes → prints `4. Dog static block`.
2. **Object creation phase (`new Dog()`):**
   - `super()` is invoked → `Animal()` constructor runs.
     - Animal instance block → `2. Animal instance block`.
     - Animal constructor body → `3. Animal constructor`.
   - Control returns to `Dog()`.
     - Dog instance block → `5. Dog instance block`.
     - Dog constructor body → `6. Dog constructor`.
3. `d.sound()` calls overridden `Dog.sound()`:
   - First `super.sound()` → `Animal makes a sound`.
   - Then `System.out.println("Dog barks")`.
4. `d.showTypes()` prints:
   - `Subclass type: Dog` (from `this.type`).
   - `Superclass type: Animal` (from `super.type`).
5. Counts: `animalCount = 1`, `dogCount = 1`.

**Final Output:**

$$
\text{Output} =
\begin{cases}
\texttt{--- Creating Dog ---} \\
\texttt{1. Animal static block} \\
\texttt{4. Dog static block} \\
\texttt{2. Animal instance block} \\
\texttt{3. Animal constructor} \\
\texttt{5. Dog instance block} \\
\texttt{6. Dog constructor} \\
\texttt{Animal makes a sound} \\
\texttt{Dog barks} \\
\texttt{Subclass type: Dog} \\
\texttt{Superclass type: Animal} \\
\texttt{Animal count: 1} \\
\texttt{Dog count: 1}
\end{cases}
$$

---

### 3.5 Constructor Chaining — Multilevel Inheritance

```java
class A {
    A() { System.out.println("A()"); }
}
class B extends A {
    B() { System.out.println("B()"); }
}
class C extends B {
    C() { System.out.println("C()"); }
}

public class ChainDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new C();
    }
}
```

**Trace:**

$$
\text{new C()} \Rightarrow \text{super()} \Rightarrow B() \Rightarrow \text{super()} \Rightarrow A() \Rightarrow \text{super()} \Rightarrow \text{Object()}
$$

**Output:** `A()`, `B()`, `C()` — printed top-down.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Tip:** When answering "What is the output?" questions, always trace the **super() call chain all the way to `Object`** before writing the answer. Static blocks are easy to forget.

---

### 3.6 Demonstrating `protected` Members

```java
package base;
public class Base {
    protected int value = 42;
    protected void show() {
        System.out.println("Base value: " + value);
    }
}

package derived;
import base.Base;
public class Derived extends Base {
    void accessValue() {
        // ✅ Allowed: accessing inherited protected member
        System.out.println("value = " + value);
        show();
    }

    void wrongAccess(Base b) {
        // ❌ NOT ALLOWED: cannot access another instance's protected via Base ref
        // System.out.println(b.value);
    }
}
```

**Rule Recap:**
- ✅ `value` is accessible inside the subclass `Derived` (via inheritance).
- ❌ `b.value` is **not** accessible because `b` is not the current subclass instance.
- ✅ `value` would be accessible if `Derived` were in the **same package** as `Base`.
