**Q1. `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`**
**Differentiate between static and instance variables in Java. Can a static variable be accessed using an object reference? Justify.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

| Feature | Static Variable | Instance Variable |
|---------|----------------|-------------------|
| Keyword | Declared with `static` | Declared without `static` |
| Belongs to | Class (one copy) | Object (one per instance) |
| Memory | Allocated once at class loading | Allocated per object creation |
| Access | `ClassName.var` (preferred) | `objectReference.var` |
| Default value | Yes | Yes |

Yes, a static variable **can** be accessed using an object reference (e.g., `obj.staticVar`), but this is **discouraged** because static members belong to the class, not the object. Modern compilers (e.g., in Java 10+) may issue a warning, suggesting direct class-name access for clarity. *(Full 3 marks)*

---

**Q2. `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`**
**Explain the four types of inner classes in Java with one-line examples.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

1. **Member Inner Class** — A non-static class declared as a member of the outer class. Requires outer instance to instantiate.
   ```java
   class Outer { class Inner { } }
   ```
2. **Static Nested Class** — A `static` class declared as a member of the outer class. Does not require an outer instance.
   ```java
   class Outer { static class Inner { } }
   ```
3. **Local Inner Class** — A class declared inside a method or block. Scope is restricted to that block.
   ```java
   void m() { class L { } }
   ```
4. **Anonymous Inner Class** — A class declared and instantiated in a single statement, typically for one-off use.
   ```java
   Runnable r = new Runnable() { public void run() { } };
   ```

