### ✦ Question A (14 Marks) `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`

**(a) [7 marks]** Explain the concept of inheritance in Java. Discuss **Single, Multilevel, and Hierarchical** inheritance with suitable Java code examples. Why does Java not support multiple inheritance through classes?

**(b) [7 marks]** Write a Java program demonstrating the use of the **`super` keyword** to:
   (i) Call the superclass constructor.
   (ii) Access a superclass field hidden by a subclass field.
   (iii) Call an overridden superclass method.
   Show the output and explain each part.

---

### Model Solution — Question A

#### (a) Inheritance Types [7 marks]

**Definition [1 mark]:**
Inheritance is an OOP mechanism that allows a class (subclass) to acquire the properties and behaviors (fields and methods) of another class (superclass) using the `extends` keyword. It promotes **code reuse** and supports **polymorphism**.

**Single Inheritance [2 marks]:**
```java
class Vehicle {
    void start() { System.out.println("Vehicle starts"); }
}
class Car extends Vehicle {
    void honk() { System.out.println("Car honks"); }
}
// Car inherits start() from Vehicle
```

**Multilevel Inheritance [2 marks]:**
```java
class Animal { void eat() { System.out.println("Eats"); } }
class Mammal extends Animal { void walk() { System.out.println("Walks"); } }
class Dog extends Mammal { void bark() { System.out.println("Barks"); } }
// Dog inherits from Mammal which inherits from Animal
```

**Hierarchical Inheritance [1 mark]:**
```java
class Shape { void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing"); } }
class Circle extends Shape { }
class Square extends Shape { }
// Multiple subclasses inherit from one superclass
```

**Why No Multiple Inheritance [1 mark]:**
Java does not support multiple inheritance through classes to avoid the **Diamond Problem** — ambiguity that arises when a class inherits two methods with the same signature from two different parents. Java resolves this using **interfaces** with `default` methods (Java 8+).

---

#### (b) `super` Keyword Demonstration [7 marks]

```java
class Employee {
    String name = "Generic Employee";
    double salary = 30000;

    Employee(String name, double salary) {
        this.name = name;
        this.salary = salary;
        System.out.println("Employee constructor called");
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name + ", Salary: " + salary);
    }
}

class Manager extends Employee {
    String name = "Generic Manager";   // hides parent field
    String department;

    Manager(String name, double salary, String dept) {
        super(name, salary);           // (i) calls superclass constructor
        this.department = dept;
        System.out.println("Manager constructor called");
    }

    @Override
    void display() {
        super.display();               // (iii) calls overridden parent method
        System.out.println("Subclass name: " + this.name);
        System.out.println("Superclass name: " + super.name);  // (ii) access hidden field
        System.out.println("Department: " + department);
    }
}

public class SuperDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Manager m = new Manager("Anu", 75000, "IT");
        System.out.println("---");
        m.display();
    }
}
```

**Output [1 mark]:**
```
Employee constructor called
Manager constructor called
---
Name: Anu, Salary: 75000.0
Subclass name: Generic Manager
Superclass name: Anu
Department: IT
```

**Explanation [3 marks]:**
- (i) `super(name, salary)` invokes the `Employee` parameterized constructor. **Must be the first line** of the `Manager` constructor.
- (ii) `super.name` retrieves the parent's `name` field, which is hidden by `Manager`'s own `name` field. The output shows `"Anu"` (from `super`) vs `"Generic Manager"` (from `this`).
- (iii) `super.display()` invokes the parent's `display()` method from within the overridden `display()` in `Manager`, enabling code reuse.

