### ✦ Question B (14 Marks) `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]` (Alternative Choice)

**(a) [7 marks]** Explain **static members** in Java — static variables, static methods, and static blocks. Write a complete program that uses a static variable as a **counter** for the number of objects created. Show the output.

**(b) [7 marks]** Discuss the **calling order of constructors** in a multilevel inheritance hierarchy. Write a Java program with classes `Grandparent`, `Parent`, and `Child` where each class has an instance initializer block, a static block, and a constructor. Show and explain the complete output when `new Child()` is executed.

---

### Model Solution — Question B

#### (a) Static Members — Counter Program [7 marks]

**Theory [3 marks]:**
- **Static Variable:** Belongs to the class; one shared copy across all objects. Stored in method area.
- **Static Method:** Can be called without an object; can access only static members directly; cannot use `this` or `super`.
- **Static Block:** Executed once at class loading time, used to initialize static data. Executes **before** the main method or any constructor.

**Program [3 marks]:**
```java
class Product {
    static int objectCount = 0;   // shared counter
    static String company = "KTU Tech";

    static {
        System.out.println("[Static Block] Class loaded. Company = " + company);
    }

    int productId;
    String productName;

    Product(int id, String name) {
        this.productId = id;
        this.productName = name;
        objectCount++;
        System.out.println("Created: " + productName + " (ID " + productId + ")");
    }

    static void showCount() {
        System.out.println("Total Products: " + objectCount);
    }
}

public class StaticCounterDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Product.showCount();              // 0
        Product p1 = new Product(1, "Laptop");
        Product p2 = new Product(2, "Phone");
        Product p3 = new Product(3, "Tablet");
        Product.showCount();              // 3
    }
}
```

**Output [1 mark]:**
```
[Static Block] Class loaded. Company = KTU Tech
Total Products: 0
Created: Laptop (ID 1)
Created: Phone (ID 2)
Created: Tablet (ID 3)
Total Products: 3
```

---

#### (b) Constructor Calling Order in Multilevel Inheritance [7 marks]

**Theory [2 marks]:**
When a subclass object is created, the JVM executes in this order:
1. **Static blocks of all classes in the hierarchy** (top-down) — runs **once** at class loading.
2. **Instance initializer blocks and constructors of the superclass** — runs first because of `super()`.
3. **Instance initializer blocks and constructors of the subclass** — runs after super completes.

**Program [3 marks]:**
```java
class Grandparent {
    static { System.out.println("1. Grandparent static block"); }
    { System.out.println("2. Grandparent instance block"); }
    Grandparent() {
        System.out.println("3. Grandparent constructor");
    }
}

class Parent extends Grandparent {
    static { System.out.println("4. Parent static block"); }
    { System.out.println("5. Parent instance block"); }
    Parent() {
        System.out.println("6. Parent constructor");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    static { System.out.println("7. Child static block"); }
    { System.out.println("8. Child instance block"); }
    Child() {
        System.out.println("9. Child constructor");
    }
}

public class ConstructorChainDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("--- main() started ---");
        new Child();
    }
}
```

**Output [1 mark]:**
```
1. Grandparent static block
4. Parent static block
7. Child static block
--- main() started ---
2. Grandparent instance block
3. Grandparent constructor
5. Parent instance block
6. Parent constructor
8. Child instance block
9. Child constructor
```

**Explanation [1 mark]:**
The static blocks fire in **top-down order** because all three classes get loaded when `new Child()` is first referenced. Then, when the object is constructed, the chain `super()` calls each ancestor's constructor (Grandparent → Parent → Child), executing instance blocks and constructors in the same order.

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Pitfalls:**
> 1. **Forgetting static blocks:** Many students list only constructors and instance blocks, missing that static blocks fire **once at class loading** — before any object exists.
> 2. **Confusing `this` and `super`:** `this` refers to the **current** object; `super` refers to the **parent class object**. They cannot be used in static context.
> 3. **`super()` placement:** Forgetting that `super()` (or `this()`) **must** be the first statement in a constructor — otherwise compile error.
> 4. **`protected` misunderstanding:** Thinking `protected` is accessible from **anywhere** via inheritance. It is accessible **only** through the subclass's own inherited reference, **not** via a parent-class object reference in a different package.
> 5. **Final reference vs final object:** Reassigning a `final` reference is illegal, but mutating the object's internal state is legal. Many students lose marks by saying "final means immutable."
> 6. **Anonymous inner class constructor:** Many students incorrectly claim anonymous classes can have constructors. They cannot — they use **instance initializer blocks** instead.
> 7. **Multiple inheritance:** Saying "Java doesn't support multiple inheritance" without mentioning **interfaces** is incomplete. Always say *"Java doesn't support multiple inheritance **through classes**; it supports it through interfaces."*

---

### Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- ✅ **`static` = class-level, one copy, loaded with class.**
- ✅ **`final` = restriction keyword** (constant / no override / no inheritance).
- ✅ **Inner classes** include Member, Static Nested, Local, and Anonymous variants.
- ✅ **Inheritance** uses `extends` for classes; Java supports Single, Multilevel, and Hierarchical.
- ✅ Java does **NOT** support Multiple/Hybrid inheritance through classes — uses interfaces instead.
- ✅ **`super`** has 3 uses: `super()` (constructor), `super.field` (hidden field), `super.method()` (overridden method).
- ✅ **`super()` must be the first statement** in a constructor; auto-inserted if not written.
- ✅ **`protected`** = package + subclass access; subclass access is **only via inheritance**.
- ✅ **Constructor execution order:** Static blocks (top-down) → Super instance block → Super constructor → Sub instance block → Sub constructor.
- ✅ **Static methods cannot be overridden** — only **hidden** (resolved at compile time by reference type).
- ✅ **`final` reference ≠ immutable object**; only the reference is fixed.
- ✅ **Anonymous inner classes** have no name and no explicit constructor.
- ✅ **Blank final variables** must be assigned exactly once in every constructor or initializer block.
- ✅ **`Object` is the root of every Java class hierarchy** (direct or indirect).
- ✅ **Method overriding** requires the same signature and covariant return type, and cannot reduce visibility.
