## SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### 2.1 The Java Exception Class Hierarchy

The entire exception framework in Java is built upon the `java.lang.Throwable` class, which is the **root** of all error and exception types.

```
java.lang.Object
   └── java.lang.Throwable
          ├── java.lang.Error          (Unrecoverable - e.g., StackOverflowError)
          └── java.lang.Exception
                 ├── java.io.IOException        (Checked)
                 ├── java.sql.SQLException      (Checked)
                 ├── java.lang.RuntimeException (Unchecked parent)
                 │       ├── ArithmeticException
                 │       ├── NullPointerException
                 │       ├── ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException
                 │       └── NumberFormatException
                 └── java.lang.ClassNotFoundException (Checked)
```

### 2.2 Checked vs Unchecked vs Error — KTU High-Yield Comparison Table

| Feature | Checked Exception | Unchecked Exception | Error |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Detection Time** | Compile-time | Run-time | Run-time |
| **Parent Class** | `Exception` (not `RuntimeException`) | `RuntimeException` | `Error` |
| **Must be Handled?** | **Yes** (mandatory `try-catch` or `throws`) | No (optional) | No (should not be handled) |
| **Caused By** | External resources (files, DB, network) | Programming bugs (logic errors) | System/JVM failures |
| **Recoverable?** | Yes | Yes | Usually No |
| **Examples** | `IOException`, `SQLException`, `ClassNotFoundException` | `ArithmeticException`, `NullPointerException`, `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` | `OutOfMemoryError`, `StackOverflowError`, `VirtualMachineError` |
| **KTU Exam Frequency** | Very High | Very High | Low |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Golden Rule for KTU Exams:** *Compiler forces you to handle CHECKED exceptions. UNCHECKED exceptions occur due to programmer mistakes and are optional to handle.*

### 2.3 The Five Keywords of Exception Handling

Java provides **5 keywords** dedicated to exception handling:

1. **`try`** – Wraps code that may throw an exception. Cannot stand alone.
2. **`catch`** – Catches and processes the exception thrown from the `try` block.
3. **`finally`** – Always executes (whether exception occurs or not). Used for cleanup.
4. **`throw`** – Used to **explicitly throw** a single exception object.
5. **`throws`** – Used in a method **signature** to declare exceptions that the method might propagate upward.

### 2.4 Syntax Blueprints (KTU-Worthy Code Skeletons)

**A. Basic try-catch:**
```java
try {
    // Code that might throw an exception
    int result = a / b;
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    // Handling code
    System.out.println("Cannot divide by zero: " + e.getMessage());
}
```

**B. try-catch-finally:**
```java
try {
    // Risky code
} catch (ExceptionType e) {
    // Handle exception
} finally {
    // Cleanup code - ALWAYS executes
    System.out.println("Cleanup performed.");
}
```

**C. throw keyword (Explicit throwing):**
```java
if (age < 18) {
    throw new IllegalArgumentException("Age must be 18+");
}
```

**D. throws keyword (Method signature):**
```java
public void readFile(String path) throws IOException, FileNotFoundException {
    FileReader fr = new FileReader(path);
    // ...
}
```

**E. Custom Exception Class:**
```java
class MyException extends Exception {
    public MyException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}
```

### 2.5 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet (Markdown Table)

| # | Concept | Syntax / Formula | Rule / Constraint |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | try block | `try { ... }` | Must be followed by `catch` or `finally` (or both) |
| 2 | catch block | `catch(ExceptionType e) { ... }` | Parameter must be a `Throwable` subtype |
| 3 | Multiple catch | `catch(A a){} catch(B b){}` | **Subclass exceptions must come BEFORE parent** |
| 4 | finally block | `finally { ... }` | Executes **always**, except `System.exit()` is called |
| 5 | throw | `throw new Exception("msg");` | Throws exactly **one** object at a time |
| 6 | throws | `void m() throws E1, E2` | Declares that method **may** propagate exceptions |
| 7 | Custom Checked | `class X extends Exception` | Must be declared/handled |
| 8 | Custom Unchecked | `class X extends RuntimeException` | No declaration/handling required |
| 9 | try-with-resources | `try (Resource r = new Resource())` | Auto-closes `AutoCloseable` resources (Java 7+) |
| 10 | Catch-all | `catch(Exception e)` | Must be the **last** catch clause |

### 2.6 Real-World Engineering Utility

| Field | Use Case of Exception Handling |
|---|---|
| **Banking Software** | Handle `InsufficientFundsException`, `InvalidAccountException` during transactions |
| **IoT/Embedded Systems** | Catch `SensorReadException`, `CommunicationTimeoutException` from device I/O |
| **Web Applications** | Handle `SQLException` (database down), `IOException` (network failure) |
| **Android/Mobile Apps** | Catch `NullPointerException` for safe UI rendering, `FileNotFoundException` for assets |
| **Data Science Pipelines** | Handle `NumberFormatException` when parsing CSV inputs, `IOException` for file streaming |
| **Aviation Systems** | Critical error handling cannot tolerate unhandled exceptions – strict `try-catch` discipline is mandatory |

