## SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Analytical Matrix & Execution Flow Derivations

### 3.1 Step-by-Step Execution Flow of `try-catch-finally`

The most critical KTU exam question is *"Trace the output of the following program."* You must master the **execution order** of statements.

> [!NOTE]
> **Universal Flow Rule:**
> 1. Statements execute sequentially inside `try`.
> 2. If an exception occurs, the **remaining code in `try` is SKIPPED**, and control jumps to the matching `catch`.
> 3. After `catch` completes, control passes to `finally`.
> 4. If **no exception occurs**, `catch` is skipped, but `finally` still runs.
> 5. After `finally`, the program continues with code **AFTER** the try-catch-finally block.

#### **Worked Example 1: Exception Occurs and is Caught**

```java
public class Demo1 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("START");
        try {
            System.out.println("A");
            int x = 10 / 0;           // ArithmeticException thrown HERE
            System.out.println("B");   // SKIPPED
        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("C - Caught: " + e.getMessage());
        } finally {
            System.out.println("D - Finally always runs");
        }
        System.out.println("END");
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Trace (Derivative Analysis):**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Step 1:} \quad & \text{Print "START"} \rightarrow \text{Output: START} \\
\text{Step 2:} \quad & \text{Enter try block} \rightarrow \text{Print "A"} \rightarrow \text{Output: A} \\
\text{Step 3:} \quad & \text{Evaluate } 10/0 \rightarrow \text{throws ArithmeticException} \\
\text{Step 4:} \quad & \text{Remaining "B" in try is SKIPPED} \\
\text{Step 5:} \quad & \text{Control jumps to matching catch block} \\
\text{Step 6:} \quad & \text{Print "C - Caught..."} \rightarrow \text{Output: C - Caught: / by zero} \\
\text{Step 7:} \quad & \text{Execute finally block} \rightarrow \text{Output: D - Finally always runs} \\
\text{Step 8:} \quad & \text{Continue after the structure} \rightarrow \text{Output: END} \\
\end{aligned}
$$

**Final Output:**
```
START
A
C - Caught: / by zero
D - Finally always runs
END
```

#### **Worked Example 2: Exception NOT Caught (Propagation)**

```java
public class Demo2 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            int[] arr = new int[5];
            arr[10] = 100;          // ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException
            System.out.println("Inside try");
        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {   // WRONG CATCH TYPE
            System.out.println("Arithmetic caught");
        } finally {
            System.out.println("Finally executes");
        }
        System.out.println("End");   // UNREACHABLE in this flow
    }
}
```

**Trace Analysis:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Step 1:} \quad & \text{Exception thrown at } arr[10] = 100 \\
\text{Step 2:} \quad & \text{Compiler cannot match catch (ArithmeticException)} \\
\text{Step 3:} \quad & \text{Control jumps to finally (which still runs)} \\
\text{Step 4:} \quad & \text{After finally, exception propagates to JVM} \\
\text{Step 5:} \quad & \text{Program terminates abnormally (stack trace printed)} \\
\end{aligned}
$$

**Final Output:**
```
Finally executes
Exception in thread "main" java.lang.ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException: 10
    at Demo2.main(Demo2.java:5)
```

> [!WARNING]
> **Critical KTU Pitfall:** If the catch type does not match the thrown exception, the `finally` block STILL executes, but the exception is NOT handled and propagates to the JVM, causing abnormal termination.

### 3.2 Step-by-Step Flow of `throw` vs `throws`

#### **Worked Example 3: Using `throw` to explicitly raise an exception**

```java
public class Validator {
    static void validateAge(int age) {
        if (age < 18) {
            throw new ArithmeticException("Not eligible to vote");
        } else {
            System.out.println("Welcome voter!");
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            validateAge(15);
        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Logical Deduction:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Step 1:} \quad & \text{call validateAge(15)} \\
\text{Step 2:} \quad & \text{Check condition: 15 < 18 \rightarrow TRUE} \\
\text{Step 3:} \quad & \text{Execute } \textbf{throw} \text{ new ArithmeticException(...)} \\
\text{Step 4:} \quad & \text{Object of ArithmeticException is created and thrown} \\
\text{Step 5:} \quad & \text{validateAge() exits abruptly to caller} \\
\text{Step 6:} \quad & \text{catch block receives the exception} \\
\text{Step 7:} \quad & \text{Print "Error: Not eligible to vote"} \\
\end{aligned}
$$

**Final Output:**
```
Error: Not eligible to vote
```

#### **Worked Example 4: Using `throws` in Method Signature**

```java
import java.io.*;
public class FileReader {
    static void readFile() throws IOException {   // DECLARATION only
        FileReader fr = new FileReader("data.txt");  // May throw IOException
        fr.read();
        fr.close();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            readFile();
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("File error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Logical Deduction:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Step 1:} \quad & \text{readFile()} \text{ declares it may propagate IOException} \\
\text{Step 2:} \quad & \text{If } data.txt \text{ is missing, JVM throws IOException} \\
\text{Step 3:} \quad & \text{Since method uses throws, exception bubbles up to main()} \\
\text{Step 4:} \quad & \text{Main method's catch handles it} \\
\text{Step 5:} \quad & \text{Print "File error: data.txt (No such file or directory)"} \\
\end{aligned}
$$

### 3.3 Step-by-Step Creation of Custom Exception

**Step 1: Define the class extending `Exception` (Checked) or `RuntimeException` (Unchecked)**

```java
// Checked Custom Exception
class InsufficientBalanceException extends Exception {
    public InsufficientBalanceException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}
```

**Step 2: Use the custom exception in business logic with `throw`**

```java
class BankAccount {
    private double balance = 5000;

    public void withdraw(double amount) throws InsufficientBalanceException {
        if (amount > balance) {
            throw new InsufficientBalanceException(
                "Insufficient balance. Available: " + balance);
        }
        balance -= amount;
        System.out.println("Withdrawal successful. New balance: " + balance);
    }
}
```

**Step 3: Handle the custom exception at the caller level**

```java
public class BankApp {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BankAccount acc = new BankAccount();
        try {
            acc.withdraw(8000);  // Exceeds balance
        } catch (InsufficientBalanceException e) {
            System.out.println("Transaction failed: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

**Complete Execution Trace:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Step 1:} \quad & \text{Create BankAccount object with balance 5000} \\
\text{Step 2:} \quad & \text{Call withdraw(8000)} \\
\text{Step 3:} \quad & \text{Check 8000 > 5000 \rightarrow TRUE} \\
\text{Step 4:} \quad & \text{Instantiate InsufficientBalanceException with custom message} \\
\text{Step 5:} \quad & \text{throw the exception object to caller (main)} \\
\text{Step 6:} \quad & \text{Caller's catch block receives the exception} \\
\text{Step 7:} \quad & \text{Print "Transaction failed: Insufficient balance..."} \\
\end{aligned}
$$

### 3.4 Analytical Matrix: When Does `finally` NOT Execute?

| Scenario | Does `finally` Run? | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| Normal execution | ✅ Yes | Always runs by default |
| Exception caught | ✅ Yes | Cleanup mandatory |
| Exception NOT caught | ✅ Yes | Still runs before propagation |
| `System.exit(0)` inside try/catch | ❌ No | JVM shuts down immediately |
| Infinite loop in try | ❌ No | Code never reaches finally |
| JVM crash / power failure | ❌ No | Hardware-level failure |
| `Runtime.getRuntime().halt(0)` | ❌ No | Forces JVM termination |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Examiner Trick Question:** "Will finally execute if System.exit() is called in try?" — **Answer: NO.** This is a famous KTU exam question.

### 3.5 Multiple Catch Clauses — Ordering Rule

```java
try {
    // some risky code
} catch (NullPointerException e) {     // Subclass first
    System.out.println("Null");
} catch (RuntimeException e) {          // Parent second
    System.out.println("Runtime");
} catch (Exception e) {                 // Grandparent last
    System.out.println("Generic");
}
```

**Mathematical Ordering Rule (KTU-Worthy):**

$$
\boxed{
\text{If } C_1 \text{ is a subclass of } C_2, \text{ then } catch(C_1) \textbf{ MUST appear BEFORE } catch(C_2)
}
$$

> [!WARNING]
> **Compilation Error Example:**
> ```java
> catch (Exception e) { }       // Parent first → COMPILATION ERROR
> catch (ArithmeticException e) { }  // Subclass second → unreachable
> ```
> This produces: *"Unreachable catch block for ArithmeticException. It is already handled by the catch block for Exception."*

### 3.6 Nested try Statements — Full Analytical Trace

```java
public class NestedDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {                                          // OUTER try
            System.out.println("Outer try start");
            try {                                      // INNER try
                int x = Integer.parseInt("abc");
            } catch (NumberFormatException e) {
                System.out.println("Inner catch: " + e.getMessage());
