**Q2. [KTU University Exam – June 2024]**
**Explain the use of the `finally` block in Java exception handling. Can the `finally` block be skipped?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

The **`finally` block** is an optional block that follows `try-catch` and contains code that **always executes**, regardless of whether an exception occurred or not. It is primarily used for **cleanup operations** like closing files, releasing database connections, or freeing network resources.

**Execution rules:**
- Runs when no exception occurs ✅
- Runs when exception is caught ✅
- Runs when exception is NOT caught ✅
- **Skipped only when** `System.exit(0)` is called or JVM crashes abruptly ❌ *(2 marks)*
- Each `try` can have **at most one** `finally` block *(1 mark)*

