### **Question B (14 Marks) — [KTU University Exam – June 2024]**

**(a) [7 marks]** Discuss the difference between `throw` and `throws` in Java with examples. Also, explain the concept of nested try statements with a suitable code example.

**(b) [7 marks]** Write a Java program that demonstrates multiple catch clauses with proper ordering. Explain why a `catch (Exception)` block must appear last among multiple catch blocks.

---

#### **Model Solution for Q.B(a):**

**Difference between `throw` and `throws`:**

| Feature | `throw` | `throws` |
|---|---|---|
| **Location** | Inside method body | In method signature |
| **Purpose** | Explicitly throws ONE exception object | Declares exceptions method may propagate |
| **Number** | Throws exactly one exception | Can declare multiple comma-separated |
| **Syntax** | `throw new E("msg")` | `void m() throws E1, E2` |

**Example of `throw`:**
```java
if (password.length() < 8)
    throw new IllegalArgumentException("Password too short");
```

**Example of `throws`:**
```java
void connectToDB() throws SQLException, ClassNotFoundException { ... }
```

**Nested try-catch Example (7 marks):**

```java
public class NestedTryDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {                                                // OUTER try
            System.out.println("Outer try: Begin");
            int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};

            try {                                            // INNER try
                System.out.println(arr[5]);                  // Throws ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException
            } catch (ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException e) {
                System.out.println("Inner catch: " + e);
            }

            String s = null;
            System.out.println(s.length());                  // Throws NullPointerException

        } catch (NullPointerException e) {
            System.out.println("Outer catch: " + e.getMessage());
        } finally {
            System.out.println("Outer finally: Always runs");
        }
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Outer try: Begin
Inner catch: java.lang.ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException: Index 5 out of bounds for length 3
Outer catch: Cannot invoke "String.length()" because "s" is null
Outer finally: Always runs
```

#### **Model Solution for Q.B(b):**

**Java Program Demonstrating Multiple Catch Clauses:**

```java
public class MultiCatchDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            String str = null;
            System.out.println(str.length());  // Throws NullPointerException

            int num = Integer.parseInt("XYZ"); // Throws NumberFormatException

            int[] arr = new int[3];
            arr[5] = 10;                      // Throws ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException

        } catch (NullPointerException e) {     // Subclass of RuntimeException
            System.out.println("1st catch - NullPointerException: " + e.getMessage());

        } catch (NumberFormatException e) {    // Subclass of RuntimeException
            System.out.println("2nd catch - NumberFormatException: " + e.getMessage());

        } catch (RuntimeException e) {         // Parent of the above two
            System.out.println("3rd catch - RuntimeException: " + e.getMessage());

        } catch (Exception e) {                // Top-most parent - MUST BE LAST
            System.out.println("4th catch - Generic Exception: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
1st catch - NullPointerException: Cannot invoke "String.length()" because "str" is null
```

**Why must `catch (Exception)` be last?**

Java's exception hierarchy is **multi-level**:

$$
\boxed{
\text{Exception} \supset \text{RuntimeException} \supset \{\text{NullPointerException}, \text{NumberFormatException}, \ldots\}
}
$$

If `catch (Exception e)` appears **first**, it would match **every** possible exception, making all subsequent `catch` blocks **unreachable**. The compiler detects this as:

> *"Unreachable catch block for NullPointerException. It is already handled by the catch block for Exception."*

Therefore, the **compiler enforces a strict rule**: catch blocks must be ordered from **most specific (subclass) to most general (parent class)**.

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Common Pitfalls (where students lose marks):**
> 1. **Forgetting `throws` clause** for checked exceptions → Compilation error (loses 2–3 marks).
> 2. **Wrong catch ordering** (parent before subclass) → Compilation error, entire program invalid.
> 3. **Confusing `throw` (object) with `throws` (declaration)** → definition question is worth 3 marks, easy to lose.
> 4. **Assuming `finally` always runs** even after `System.exit(0)` → Wrong, 0 marks on that sub-question.
> 5. **Forgetting to call `super(message)`** in custom exception constructor → Program works but `getMessage()` returns `null`, loses 1 mark.
> 6. **Writing `catch` without parentheses around exception variable** → Syntax error.

