## SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### 2.1 The Two Event Handling Mechanisms (Foundational Concept)

Java provides **two distinct mechanisms** for handling events. The KTU syllabus explicitly asks about both:

#### Mechanism 1: Inheritance-Based Event Handling (Legacy / JDK 1.0)

- The container class (usually the `Applet` or `Frame`) **inherits** from an adapter class.
- The container **overrides** event-handling methods like `actionPerformed()`, `keyPressed()`, `mouseClicked()`.
- All components inside the container delegate their events **upward** to the container.
- This is the **older, monolithic** approach.

> [!WARNING]
> **Why KTU prefers Delegation Model:** The inheritance-based approach violates the OOP principle of *composition over inheritance*. It forces the container to handle every event for every child, leading to massive `if-else` ladders inside a single method (e.g., identifying which button was clicked via `if(e.getSource() == button1)`).

#### Mechanism 2: Delegation-Based Event Handling (Modern / JDK 1.1+)

- Events are dispatched **only to interested, registered listeners**.
- A component can have **multiple listeners**; a listener can serve **multiple sources**.
- The model follows the **Observer design pattern** exactly.
- This is the **mandatory** approach in all modern Java AWT/Swing code.

### 2.2 The Delegation Event Model — Architectural Deep Dive

The Delegation Event Model has **four key participants**. Every KTU question on this topic expects you to know all four.

#### 2.2.1 Event (Event Object)

- A subclass of `java.util.EventObject` (or AWT's `java.awt.AWTEvent` for AWT events).
- Encapsulates all information about the occurrence: source component, coordinates, modifiers, timestamp, etc.
- **Immutable** by convention — read-only after creation.

#### 2.2.2 Event Source

- A GUI component (e.g., `Button`, `TextField`, `JButton`) that:
  1. **Detects** that an event has occurred.
  2. **Creates** an event object representing that occurrence.
  3. **Invokes** the registered listener's handler method, passing the event object.
- Provides `addXxxListener()` and `removeXxxListener()` methods for registration.

#### 2.2.3 Event Listener

- An **interface** (e.g., `ActionListener`, `MouseListener`) that the handler class **implements**.
- Declares one or more abstract handler methods (e.g., `void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)`).
- Acts as a **contract** — the source knows only that the listener *can* receive events of a certain type.

#### 2.2.4 Event Handler

- The **concrete implementation** of the listener method in the handler class.
- Contains the actual business logic to be executed.

### 2.3 The Event Class Hierarchy (Diagram in Section 4)

All AWT events ultimately extend `java.awt.AWTEvent`, which itself extends `java.util.EventObject`. The major categories:

| Event Class | Package | Triggered By | Listener Interface |
|---|---|---|---|
| `ActionEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Clicking button, selecting menu, pressing Enter in text field | `ActionListener` |
| `MouseEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Mouse press, release, click, enter, exit, move, drag | `MouseListener`, `MouseMotionListener` |
| `KeyEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Pressing/releasing a key | `KeyListener` |
| `FocusEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Component gaining/losing focus | `FocusListener` |
| `WindowEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Opening/closing/iconifying window | `WindowListener` |
| `ItemEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Selecting/deselecting checkbox/radio/list item | `ItemListener` |
| `TextEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Text value changes | `TextListener` |
| `ComponentEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Component shown/hidden/moved/resized | `ComponentListener` |
| `AdjustmentEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Scrollbar adjusted | `AdjustmentListener` |
| `ContainerEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Component added/removed from container | `ContainerListener` |
| `PaintEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Repaint request (internal, mostly hidden) | (none) |
| `InputEvent` | `java.awt.event` | Abstract superclass of `MouseEvent` & `KeyEvent` | (abstract) |

### 2.4 Sources of Events — Which Component Fires What?

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU High-Yield Mapping:** The KTU exam frequently asks "Which event is generated by which component?" Memorize the following mappings:

- **Button** → `ActionEvent` (on click)
- **Checkbox** (older AWT `Checkbox`) → `ItemEvent` (on check/uncheck)
- **CheckboxMenuItem** → `ItemEvent`
- **Choice** (dropdown) → `ItemEvent` (on selection)
- **List** (AWT `List`) → `ActionEvent` (on double-click) AND `ItemEvent` (on selection)
- **MenuItem** → `ActionEvent`
- **Scrollbar** → `AdjustmentEvent`
- **TextField** → `ActionEvent` (on Enter key) AND `TextEvent` (on text change)
- **TextArea** → `TextEvent`
- **Window** → `WindowEvent` (open, close, iconify, etc.)
- **Any Component** → `MouseEvent`, `KeyEvent`, `FocusEvent`, `ComponentEvent`

### 2.5 Event Listener Interfaces — Complete Catalogue

| Listener Interface | Handler Methods (Abstract) | Adapter Class (Convenience) |
|---|---|---|
| `ActionListener` | `actionPerformed(ActionEvent)` | None (only one method) |
| `MouseListener` | `mousePressed`, `mouseReleased`, `mouseEntered`, `mouseExited`, `mouseClicked` | `MouseAdapter` |
| `MouseMotionListener` | `mouseDragged`, `mouseMoved` | `MouseMotionAdapter` |
| `KeyListener` | `keyPressed`, `keyReleased`, `keyTyped` | `KeyAdapter` |
| `FocusListener` | `focusGained`, `focusLost` | `FocusAdapter` |
| `WindowListener` | `windowOpened`, `windowClosing`, `windowClosed`, `windowIconified`, `windowDeiconified`, `windowActivated`, `windowDeactivated` | `WindowAdapter` |
| `ItemListener` | `itemStateChanged` | None (only one method) |
| `TextListener` | `textValueChanged` | None (only one method) |
| `ComponentListener` | `componentShown`, `componentHidden`, `componentMoved`, `componentResized` | `ComponentAdapter` |
| `ContainerListener` | `componentAdded`, `componentRemoved` | `ContainerAdapter` |
| `AdjustmentListener` | `adjustmentValueChanged` | None |

> [!NOTE]
> **The Adapter Pattern Insight:** When a listener interface declares multiple methods (e.g., `MouseListener` has 5), you are *forced* to implement all of them even if you only care about one. Java provides **Adapter classes** — empty default implementations — so you can override only the methods you need. Adapters exist only for interfaces with **two or more** methods.

### 2.6 KTU Formula Cheat Sheet — Event Registration Syntax

There is a **uniform registration pattern** that applies to every event category. The KTU board examiner often tests this directly:

$$\text{component.add}\text{[EventType]}\text{Listener(listenerObject);}$$

The actual forms for each event type are summarized below:

| Event Type | Registration Method Signature |
|---|---|
| Action | `void addActionListener(ActionListener l)` |
| Mouse | `void addMouseListener(MouseListener l)` |
| Mouse Motion | `void addMouseMotionListener(MouseMotionListener l)` |
| Key | `void addKeyListener(KeyListener l)` |
| Focus | `void addFocusListener(FocusListener l)` |
| Window | `void addWindowListener(WindowListener l)` |
| Item | `void addItemListener(ItemListener l)` |
| Text | `void addTextListener(TextListener l)` |
| Component | `void addComponentListener(ComponentListener l)` |
| Container | `void addContainerListener(ContainerListener l)` |
| Adjustment | `void addAdjustmentListener(AdjustmentListener l)` |

### 2.7 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **GUI-based Industrial Control Panels** (SCADA systems): Use event handling for sensor inputs.
- **Banking Software**: ActionEvents drive every transaction initiation.
- **Web Browsers (in-browser Java applets, legacy)**: Mouse and Key events drive all interactivity.
- **IDE Plugins (NetBeans/Eclipse)** built in Swing: Heavy use of property change, focus, and key events.
- **Game Development**: KeyListener and MouseMotionListener for player input.

