## SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Implementation Walkthrough & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 The Five Mandatory Steps to Use the Delegation Event Model

Every event-handling program in Java (and every KTU exam answer) follows exactly this five-step sequence. Master this skeleton and you can answer **any** 14-mark question on this topic.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The Five-Step Skeleton (Memorize This):**
> 1. **Implement** the appropriate `XxxListener` interface in your class.
> 2. **Provide the implementation** for every method declared by the interface (or extend the adapter class).
> 3. **Create** the GUI component (the event source).
> 4. **Register** the listener with the source via `addXxxListener()`.
> 5. **Define** the event-handling logic inside the implemented method.

### 3.2 Worked Example #1: ActionEvent (The Classic Button-Click)

Let us exhaustively walk through the canonical "Button Click Counter" example.

**Requirement:** Build a frame containing a button labeled "Click Me" and a label. Each click on the button should increment and display a counter.

**Step 1: Import the required packages.**

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
```

**Step 2: Declare the class and implement the listener interface.**

```java
public class ButtonClickCounter extends Frame implements ActionListener {
    // class fields declared here
    private Label counterLabel;
    private Button clickButton;
    private int count;
```

**Step 3: Implement the constructor — set up the GUI.**

```java
    public ButtonClickCounter() {
        // Initialize count
        count = 0;

        // Create the source component
        clickButton = new Button("Click Me");

        // Create the display component
        counterLabel = new Label("Count: 0");

        // Set a layout for the frame
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        // Add components to the frame
        add(clickButton);
        add(counterLabel);

        // Set frame properties
        setTitle("Delegation Event Model Demo");
        setSize(300, 150);
        setVisible(true);
```

**Step 4: Register the listener with the source — THE CRITICAL STEP.**

```java
        // This single line wires the source to the listener
        clickButton.addActionListener(this);
    }
```

**Step 5: Provide the event-handling implementation.**

```java
    // The handler method - contains the business logic
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        count = count + 1;
        counterLabel.setText("Count: " + count);
    }
```

**Step 6: Provide a `main` method to launch.**

```java
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new ButtonClickCounter();
    }
}
```

**Step 7 (Destructor / Cleanup — best practice, often skipped in KTU answers but KTU examiners appreciate it):**

```java
    // Override windowClosing to allow graceful exit
    // Note: requires implementing WindowListener or extending WindowAdapter
    // For brevity in the model answer, the listener is sometimes separated.
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Trace of Execution:**
> 1. User clicks the button.
> 2. AWT detects the click and constructs an `ActionEvent` object (source = `clickButton`, id = `ACTION_PERFORMED`).
> 3. AWT iterates through the list of registered `ActionListener`s for that button.
> 4. AWT calls `actionPerformed(event)` on each listener.
> 5. Our `actionPerformed` increments `count` and updates the label.

### 3.3 Worked Example #2: MouseListener with MouseAdapter

**Requirement:** Change the background color of a frame when the mouse enters it, and revert when the mouse exits.

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class MouseHoverColor extends Frame {
    public MouseHoverColor() {
        setTitle("Mouse Hover Demo");
        setSize(400, 300);
        setBackground(Color.LIGHT_GRAY);

        // Register a MouseListener using an anonymous inner class
        // extending MouseAdapter (covers all 5 methods with empty bodies)
        addMouseListener(new MouseAdapter() {
            @Override
            public void mouseEntered(MouseEvent e) {
                setBackground(Color.YELLOW);
            }

            @Override
            public void mouseExited(MouseEvent e) {
                setBackground(Color.LIGHT_GRAY);
            }
        });

        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new MouseHoverColor();
    }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Why MouseAdapter?** `MouseListener` has 5 methods. Without an adapter, you would have to write empty bodies for `mousePressed`, `mouseReleased`, and `mouseClicked` even though you don't care about them. `MouseAdapter` provides empty defaults, so you override only what you need — a textbook application of the **Adapter design pattern**.

### 3.4 Worked Example #3: WindowListener (Closing the Window Gracefully)

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class GracefulClose extends Frame {
    public GracefulClose() {
        setTitle("Graceful Close Demo");
        setSize(300, 200);

        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            @Override
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {
                System.exit(0);  // Terminates the JVM
            }
        });

        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new GracefulClose();
    }
}
```

### 3.5 Worked Example #4: KeyListener — Capturing Key Presses

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class KeyLogger extends Frame implements KeyListener {
    private TextArea displayArea;

    public KeyLogger() {
        setTitle("Key Event Demo");
        setSize(400, 300);
        setLayout(new BorderLayout());

        displayArea = new TextArea();
        add(displayArea, BorderLayout.CENTER);

        // Register for key events on the text area
        displayArea.addKeyListener(this);

        setVisible(true);
    }

    public void keyTyped(KeyEvent e) {
        displayArea.append("Typed: " + e.getKeyChar() + "\n");
    }

    public void keyPressed(KeyEvent e) {
        displayArea.append("Pressed: " + e.getKeyCode() + "\n");
    }

    public void keyReleased(KeyEvent e) {
        // Empty - not used in this example
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new KeyLogger();
    }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Important distinction between `keyPressed` and `keyTyped`:**
> - `keyPressed`/`keyReleased` fire for **every** key (including non-character keys like Shift, Ctrl, F1–F12). They receive a `keyCode` (an `int`).
> - `keyTyped` fires **only for character-producing keys**. It receives a `keyChar` (a `char`).
> - This distinction is a KTU favourite.

### 3.6 Analytical Matrix — Multi-Listener Registration

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Crucial Concept:** A single source can be registered with **multiple listeners**. The order of invocation is **not guaranteed** by the AWT specification, but in practice it is the order of registration.

```java
Button b = new Button("Multi");

// Register TWO different listeners
b.addActionListener(new ListenerOne());
b.addActionListener(new ListenerTwo());

// Both listeners will be notified when the button is clicked.
```

Conversely, a single listener can be registered with **multiple sources**:

```java
ActionListener shared = new SharedHandler();
b1.addActionListener(shared);
b2.addActionListener(shared);
b3.addActionListener(shared);

// shared.actionPerformed() must use e.getSource()
// to determine WHICH button was clicked
```

### 3.7 `getSource()` vs `getActionCommand()` — Disambiguation

When a single listener handles multiple buttons, you need to identify the source. Two techniques are used:

#### Technique 1: `e.getSource()` — uses object identity

```java
public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
    if (e.getSource() == button1) {
        // handle button1
    } else if (e.getSource() == button2) {
        // handle button2
    }
}
```

#### Technique 2: `e.getActionCommand()` — uses the label string

```java
public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
    String cmd = e.getActionCommand();
    if (cmd.equals("Submit")) {
        // handle submit
    } else if (cmd.equals("Cancel")) {
        // handle cancel
    }
}
```

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Pitfall:** `e.getActionCommand()` returns the **button's label by default**. If you set the action command explicitly via `button.setActionCommand("customCmd")`, it returns that custom string instead.

### 3.8 Comprehensive Comparison Table: Inheritance vs Delegation Model

| Aspect | Inheritance Model (JDK 1.0) | Delegation Model (JDK 1.1+) |
|---|---|---|
| Approach | Container overrides event methods | Listener interface is implemented |
| Coupling | Tight (container must know all events) | Loose (decoupled) |
| Multiple handlers per event | Not directly possible | Yes (multiple listeners per source) |
| Code organization | One large method with if-else | One method per event type |
| Inheritance requirement | Must extend a specific class | Must implement an interface (flexible) |
| Modern relevance | Legacy / discouraged | **Standard / mandatory** |
| Maps to design pattern | None specifically | **Observer Pattern** |

### 3.9 Full Skeleton Template (For 14-Mark Answers)

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class EventHandlerTemplate extends Frame
        implements ActionListener, WindowListener {

    private Button btn;
    private TextField tf;

    public EventHandlerTemplate() {
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        setTitle("Template");
        setSize(400, 200);

        tf = new TextField(20);
        btn = new Button("OK");

        add(tf);
        add(btn);

        // === STEP 4: REGISTER THE LISTENERS ===
        btn.addActionListener(this);
        tf.addActionListener(this);
        addWindowListener(this);

        setVisible(true);
    }

    // === STEP 5: HANDLE THE EVENTS ===
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        if (e.getSource() == btn) {
            System.out.println("Button clicked, text is: " + tf.getText());
        } else if (e.getSource() == tf) {
            System.out.println("Enter pressed in text field");
        }
    }

    // Required WindowListener methods
    public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) { System.exit(0); }
    public void windowOpened(WindowEvent e) {}
    public void windowClosed(WindowEvent e) {}
    public void windowIconified(WindowEvent e) {}
    public void windowDeiconified(WindowEvent e) {}
    public void windowActivated(WindowEvent e) {}
    public void windowDeactivated(WindowEvent e) {}

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new EventHandlerTemplate();
    }
}
```

