## SECTION 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### PART A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

**Q1. [KTU University Exam — June 2024]**  
**Differentiate between the two event handling mechanisms available in Java.**

**Model Answer:**

The two event handling mechanisms in Java are:

**1. Inheritance-based Event Handling (JDK 1.0):**
- The container class extends an AWT component class and overrides event-handling methods such as `handleEvent()` or `action()`.
- All events from all child components are automatically sent to the container.
- Uses a single large method with `if-else` or `switch` to identify the event source and type.
- **Drawback:** Tight coupling; one method handles everything.

**2. Delegation-based Event Handling (JDK 1.1+):**
- The class implements a specific listener interface (e.g., `ActionListener`).
- The event source delegates events to registered listeners.
- Each event type has its own dedicated handler method.
- **Advantage:** Loose coupling, multiple listeners per source, follows the Observer design pattern.

The delegation model is the modern, preferred approach in all current Java AWT and Swing programs.

---

**Q2. [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]**  
**List any four Event Listener interfaces and their corresponding Adapter classes from the `java.awt.event` package.**

**Model Answer:**

| Listener Interface | Adapter Class |
|---|---|
| `MouseListener` | `MouseAdapter` |
| `MouseMotionListener` | `MouseMotionAdapter` |
| `KeyListener` | `KeyAdapter` |
| `WindowListener` | `WindowAdapter` |
| `FocusListener` | `FocusAdapter` |
| `ComponentListener` | `ComponentAdapter` |
| `ContainerListener` | `ContainerAdapter` |

**Note:** Interfaces with only one method (e.g., `ActionListener`, `ItemListener`, `TextListener`, `AdjustmentListener`) do **not** have adapter classes because the single method can be implemented directly without empty placeholders.

