**Question B (14 Marks) [Alternative Choice]**

**(a) [7 Marks]** Explain **Event Classes** and **Sources of Events** in Java AWT. Discuss the hierarchy of AWT event classes with a suitable diagram.

**(b) [7 Marks]** Write a Java AWT program to demonstrate the use of `KeyListener`. The program should display each key typed by the user in a `TextArea`.

**Model Answer for Part (a):**

**Event Classes in Java AWT:**

An event class is a Java class that represents a specific type of event. Every event class encapsulates the details of one particular user or system action. All AWT event classes extend `java.awt.AWTEvent`, which in turn extends `java.util.EventObject`.

**Hierarchy of AWT Event Classes:**

```
java.util.EventObject
        |
        v
java.awt.AWTEvent
        |
        +---> ActionEvent
        +---> ItemEvent
        +---> AdjustmentEvent
        +---> TextEvent
        +---> ComponentEvent
        |         |
        |         +---> ContainerEvent
        |         +---> FocusEvent
        |         +---> WindowEvent
        |         +---> PaintEvent
        |
        +---> InputEvent
                  |
                  +---> KeyEvent
                  +---> MouseEvent
```

**Major Event Classes and Their Triggers:**

| Event Class | Triggered When |
|---|---|
| `ActionEvent` | Button is clicked, menu item is selected, Enter is pressed in a text field |
| `ItemEvent` | A checkbox, radio button, list item, or choice is selected/deselected |
| `KeyEvent` | A key is pressed, released, or typed on the keyboard |
| `MouseEvent` | The mouse is pressed, released, clicked, entered, exited, moved, or dragged |
| `WindowEvent` | A window is opened, closed, iconified, deiconified, activated, or deactivated |
| `FocusEvent` | A component gains or loses keyboard focus |
| `TextEvent` | The value of a text component changes |
| `AdjustmentEvent` | A scrollbar is adjusted |
| `ComponentEvent` | A component is moved, resized, shown, or hidden |
| `ContainerEvent` | A component is added to or removed from a container |

**Sources of Events:**

A *source* is a GUI component that can generate events. The mapping between sources and event types is as follows:

| Source Component | Event Generated |
|---|---|
| `Button` | `ActionEvent` |
| `Checkbox`, `CheckboxMenuItem` | `ItemEvent` |
| `Choice` (dropdown) | `ItemEvent` |
| `List` | `ActionEvent` (on double-click), `ItemEvent` (on selection) |
| `MenuItem` | `ActionEvent` |
| `Scrollbar` | `AdjustmentEvent` |
| `TextField` | `ActionEvent` (on Enter), `TextEvent` (on text change) |
| `TextArea` | `TextEvent` |
| `Window` | `WindowEvent` |
| Any `Component` | `KeyEvent`, `MouseEvent`, `FocusEvent`, `ComponentEvent` |

A source registers listeners via the `addXxxListener()` method and removes them via `removeXxxListener()`.

---

**Model Answer for Part (b):**

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class KeyLogger extends Frame implements KeyListener {
    private TextArea displayArea;
    private Label infoLabel;

    public KeyLogger() {
        setTitle("Key Event Demonstration");
        setSize(500, 400);
        setLayout(new BorderLayout());

        infoLabel = new Label("Type something - keys will be logged below");
        displayArea = new TextArea();
        displayArea.setEditable(false);

        add(infoLabel, BorderLayout.NORTH);
        add(displayArea, BorderLayout.CENTER);

        // Register the listener with the TextArea
        displayArea.addKeyListener(this);

        // Add an item listener to displayArea for closing window
        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {
                System.exit(0);
            }
        });

        setVisible(true);
        displayArea.requestFocus();  // Ensure TextArea has focus
    }

    // Handler for key typed events
    public void keyTyped(KeyEvent e) {
        displayArea.append("Key Typed: '" + e.getKeyChar() + "'\n");
    }

    // Handler for key pressed events
    public void keyPressed(KeyEvent e) {
        displayArea.append("Key Pressed: code = " + e.getKeyCode() + "\n");
    }

    // Handler for key released events
    public void keyReleased(KeyEvent e) {
        displayArea.append("Key Released: code = " + e.getKeyCode() + "\n");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new KeyLogger();
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**

- The class implements `KeyListener`, which requires three methods: `keyTyped`, `keyPressed`, `keyReleased`.
- A `TextArea` is used as both the source (to receive keys) and the display (to log them).
- The `KeyEvent` object provides:
  - `e.getKeyChar()` → the character typed (used in `keyTyped`).
  - `e.getKeyCode()` → the integer code of the key (used in `keyPressed`/`keyReleased`).
- `displayArea.requestFocus()` ensures the `TextArea` receives keyboard input when the program starts.
- The three methods log every key event, demonstrating the difference between `keyPressed` (fires for all keys) and `keyTyped` (fires only for character-producing keys).

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Pitfalls:**
> 1. **Forgetting to register the listener** — students often write the `actionPerformed` method but forget the `addActionListener(this)` call. This results in **zero** event handling — a guaranteed 0 marks for the implementation part.
> 2. **Implementing the wrong interface** — using `MouseListener` when `ActionListener` is needed, or vice versa. Always match the source component to the appropriate listener type.
> 3. **Not overriding ALL methods of the interface** — Java will not compile if even one method is missing (unless an adapter class is used). Watch for this in your code.
> 4. **Confusing `keyPressed` and `keyTyped`** — `keyPressed` reports a `keyCode` (int) for every key; `keyTyped` reports a `keyChar` (char) for character keys only.
> 5. **Mixing up `getSource()` and `getActionCommand()`** — `getSource()` returns an `Object` (the component); `getActionCommand()` returns a `String` (the label by default).
> 6. **Writing only the class header without `setVisible(true)`** — the frame will never display. Always include this in the constructor.
> 7. **Not handling the `WindowListener` for closing** — the program will not exit when the user clicks the close button, often leading to deduction.

