### Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **High-Density Revision Checklist:**

- ✅ Event handling is the mechanism that controls events and decides what happens when an event occurs.
- ✅ An **event** is an object describing a state change in a GUI component.
- ✅ The two event handling mechanisms are: **Inheritance-based** (JDK 1.0) and **Delegation-based** (JDK 1.1+).
- ✅ The Delegation Event Model is the modern, preferred approach — it follows the **Observer design pattern**.
- ✅ Four key participants: **Event**, **Event Source**, **Event Listener**, **Event Handler**.
- ✅ The **event source** generates events and provides `addXxxListener()` and `removeXxxListener()` methods.
- ✅ The **event listener** is an interface that the handler class implements.
- ✅ The **event handler** is the method that actually responds to the event.
- ✅ All AWT events extend `java.awt.AWTEvent` (which extends `java.util.EventObject`).
- ✅ Adapter classes (e.g., `MouseAdapter`, `KeyAdapter`, `WindowAdapter`) exist for interfaces with 2+ methods and provide empty default implementations.
- ✅ `ActionListener` has only `actionPerformed` method — no adapter exists.
- ✅ `keyPressed` reports `keyCode` (int); `keyTyped` reports `keyChar` (char).
- ✅ `e.getSource()` returns the **object** that fired the event.
- ✅ `e.getActionCommand()` returns the **label string** of the source (by default).
- ✅ Multiple listeners can be registered on a single source; one listener can handle multiple sources.
- ✅ Common sources: `Button` → `ActionEvent`; `TextField` → `ActionEvent` + `TextEvent`; `Checkbox` → `ItemEvent`; `Window` → `WindowEvent`.
- ✅ Common listeners: `ActionListener`, `MouseListener`, `KeyListener`, `WindowListener`, `ItemListener`, `FocusListener`, `TextListener`, `AdjustmentListener`, `ComponentListener`, `ContainerListener`.
- ✅ Always use `addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() { ... })` for graceful close.
- ✅ The five-step implementation recipe: **import → implement → instantiate → register → handle**.

